# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: airsoft-gun
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The **.40 S&W** is a rimless pistol cartridge developed jointly by American firearms manufacturers Smith & Wesson and Winchester in 1990.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was developed as a law enforcement cartridge designed to duplicate the performance of the Federal Bureau of Investigation's (FBI) reduced-velocity 10mm Auto cartridge which could be retrofitted into medium-frame (9 mm size) semi-automatic handguns.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] It uses 0.40-inch-diameter (10 mm) bullets typically ranging in weight from 105 to 200 grains (6.8 to 13.0 g).
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] In the aftermath of the 1986 FBI Miami shootout, in which two FBI special agents were killed and five wounded, the FBI started the process of testing 9×19mm Parabellum and .45 ACP ammunition in preparation to replace its standard-issue revolver with a semi-automatic pistol.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The semi-automatic pistol offered two advantages over the revolver: increased ammunition capacity and increased ease of reloading during a gunfight.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The FBI was satisfied with the performance of its .38 Special +P 158 gr (10.2 g) lead semi-wadcutter hollowpoint (LSWCHP) cartridge ("FBI load") based on decades of dependable performance.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Ammunition for the new semi-automatic pistol had to deliver terminal performance equal or superior to the .38 Special FBI load.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The FBI developed a series of practically oriented tests involving eight test events that they believed reasonably represented the kinds of situations that FBI agents commonly encountered in shooting incidents.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] During tests of the 9×19mm and .45 ACP ammunition, the unit chief of the FBI Firearms Training Unit, John Hall, decided to include tests of the 10mm Auto cartridge, supplying his own Colt Delta Elite 10mm semi-automatic, and personally hand-loaded ammunition.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The FBI's tests revealed that a 170–180 gr (11.0–11.7 g) JHP 10mm bullet, propelled between 900–1,000 ft/s (270–300 m/s), achieved desired terminal performance without the heavy recoil associated with conventional 10mm ammunition (1,300–1,400 ft/s (400–430 m/s)).
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The FBI contacted Smith & Wesson and requested that it design a handgun to FBI specifications, based on the existing large-frame Smith & Wesson Model 4506 .45 ACP handgun, that would reliably function with the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm ammunition.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] During this collaboration with the FBI, S&W realized that downsizing the 10mm full-power to meet the FBI's medium-velocity specification meant less powder and more airspace in the case.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] They found that by removing the airspace they could shorten the 10mm case enough to fit within their medium-frame 9mm handguns and load it with a 180 gr (11.7 g) JHP bullet to produce ballistic performance identical to the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] S&W then teamed with Winchester to produce a new cartridge, the .40 S&W.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] It uses a small pistol primer whereas the 10mm cartridge uses a large pistol primer.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge debuted January 17, 1990, along with the new Smith & Wesson Model 4006 pistol, although it was several months before the pistols were available for purchase.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Austrian manufacturer Glock Ges.m.b.H. were commercially available ahead of Smith & Wesson in 1990, with pistols chambered in .40 S&W (the Glock 22 and Glock 23) which were announced a week before the 4006.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Glock's rapid introduction was aided by its engineering of a pistol chambered in 10mm Auto, the Glock 20, only a short time earlier.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Since the .40 S&W uses the same bore diameter and case head as the 10mm Auto, it was merely a matter of adapting the 10mm design to the shorter 9×19mm Parabellum frames.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The new guns and ammunition were an immediate success, and pistols in the new caliber were adopted by several law enforcement agencies around the nation, including the FBI, which adopted the Glock pistol in .40 S&W in May 1997.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The popularity of the .40 S&W accelerated with the passage of the now-expired Federal Assault Weapons Ban of 1994, which prohibited sales of pistol or rifle magazines that could hold more than ten cartridges, regardless of caliber.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Several U.S. states, and a number of local governments, also banned or regulated so-called "high-capacity" magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] As a result, many new firearm buyers limited to purchasing pistols with a maximum magazine capacity of 10 rounds chose pistols in the .40 S&W chambering instead of smaller-diameter cartridges such as the 9×19mm (9mm Luger or 9mm Parabellum).
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W case length and overall cartridge length are shortened, but other dimensions except for case web and wall thickness remain identical to the 10mm Auto.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Both cartridges headspace on the mouth of the case.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Thus in a semi-auto, they are not interchangeable.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Fired from a 10mm semi-auto, the .40 Smith & Wesson cartridge will headspace on the extractor and the bullet will jump a 0.142 inches (3.6 mm) freebore just like a .38 Special fired from a .357 Magnum revolver.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] If the cartridge is not held by the extractor, the chances for a ruptured primer are great.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Smith & Wesson does make a double-action revolver (the Model 610) that can fire either cartridge via use of moon clips.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] A single-action revolver in the .38–40 chambering can also fire .40 or 10mm rounds provided it is equipped with a correctly sized cylinder.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Some .40 caliber handguns can be converted to 9mm with a special purpose-made barrel, magazine change, and other parts.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] In 2015, the FBI announced they were going back to 9mm ammunition, citing advancements in ballistic technology and increased accuracy in a gunfight.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The FBI also found that .40 S&W rounds were causing excessive wear on pistols and were harder to control for some agents.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] This has caused a substantial contribution to the .40 S&W's decline in popularity with law enforcement in the US.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has a 1.25 ml (19.3 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 406 millimetres (16.0 in), with 6 grooves, land diameter 9.91 mm, groove diameter 10.17 mm, and land width 3.05 mm, and the primer type is small pistol.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] According to the official C.I.P. guidelines, the .40 S&W case can handle up to 225 MPa (32,600 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] In C.I.P.-regulated countries, every pistol/cartridge combo has to be proofed at 130% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The SAAMI pressure limit for the .40 S&W is set at 241.32 MPa (35,001 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge has been popular with law enforcement agencies in the United States, Canada, Australia, and Brazil.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] While possessing nearly identical accuracy, drift and drop as the 9mm Parabellum, it has an energy advantage over the 9mm Parabellum and .45 ACP, and a more manageable recoil than the 10mm Auto cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Marshall & Sanow (and other hydrostatic shock proponents) contend that with good jacketed hollow point bullets, the more energetic loads for the .40 S&W can also create hydrostatic shock in human-sized living targets.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Based on the ideal terminal ballistic performance in ordnance gelatin during lab testing in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the .40 S&W earned status as "the ideal cartridge for personal defense and law enforcement".
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Ballistically the .40 S&W is almost identical to the .38-40 Winchester introduced in 1874, as they share the same bullet diameter and bullet weight, and have similar muzzle velocities.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The energy of the .40 S&W exceeds standard-pressure .45 ACP loadings, generating between 350 foot-pounds (470 J) and 500 foot-pounds (680 J) of energy, depending on bullet weight.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Both the .40 S&W and the 9mm Parabellum operate at a 35,000 pounds per square inch (240 MPa) SAAMI maximum, compared to a 21,000 pounds per square inch (140 MPa) maximum for .45 ACP.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] .40 S&W pistols with standard (not extended) double-stack magazines can hold as many as 16 cartridges.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] While not displacing the 9mm Parabellum, the .40 S&W is commonly used in law enforcement applications in keeping with its origin with the FBI.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Select U.S. special operations units have available the .40 S&W and .45 ACP for their pistols.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The United States Coast Guard, having dual duties as maritime law enforcement and military deployments, has adopted the SIG Sauer P229R DAK in .40 S&W as their standard sidearm.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] However, as of 2020, the Coast Guard has adopted the Glock 19 GEN5 MOS as its new sidearm.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Numerous federal and local law enforcement agencies are currently in the process of transitioning from .40 S&W to 9mm, most notably the FBI, who adopted 9mm firearms in 2015.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Customs and Border Protection adopted 9mm Glock handguns, replacing the .40 S&W Heckler & Koch P2000 CBP was previously using.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was originally loaded at subsonic velocity (984.25 ft/s (300.00 m/s)) with a 180 grains (11.7 g) bullet.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Since its introduction, various loads have been created, with the majority being either 155, 165 or 180 gr (10.0, 10.7 or 11.7 g).
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] However, there are some bullets with weights as light as 135 gr (8.7 g) and as heavy as 200 gr (13.0 g).
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Cor-Bon and Winchester both offer a 135 gr (8.7 g) JHP and Cor-Bon also offers a 140 gr (9.1 g) Barnes XPB hollow-point.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has been noted in a number of cartridge case failures involving older Glock pistols, due to the relatively large area of unsupported case head in those barrels, given its allowed chamber pressure level.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] The feed ramp on the Glock .40 S&W pistols is larger than on other Glocks, which leaves the rear bottom of the case unsupported, and it is in this unsupported area that the cases fail.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Most, but not all, of the failures have occurred with reloaded or remanufactured ammunition.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] Cartridges loaded at or above the SAAMI pressure, or slightly oversized cases which fire slightly out of battery are often considered to be the cause of these failures, which are commonly referred to as "kaBooms" or "kB!" for short.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] While these case failures do not often injure the person holding the pistol, the venting of high-pressure gas tends to eject the magazine out of the magazine well in a spectacular fashion, and usually destroys the pistol.
[src:airsoft-gun/40-s-w] In some cases, the barrel will also fail, blowing the top of the chamber off.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In firearms technology, an **action** is the functional mechanism of a breechloading firearm that handles (loads, locks, fires, extracts, and ejects) the ammunition cartridges, or the method by which that mechanism works.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Actions can be categorized in several ways, including single action versus double action, break action versus lever-action, pump-action, bolt-action, among many other types.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The term action can also include short, long, and magnum if it is in reference to the length of the rifle's receiver and the length of the bolt.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The short action rifle usually can accommodate a cartridge length of 2.8 in (71 mm) or smaller.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The long action rifle can accommodate a cartridge of 3.34 in (85 mm), and the magnum action rifle can accommodate cartridges of 3.6 in (91 mm).
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Actions are technically not present on muzzleloaders, as all those are single-shot firearms with a closed off breech with the powder and projectile manually loaded from the muzzle.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Instead, the muzzleloader ignition mechanism is referred to as the *lock* (e.g. matchlock, wheellock, flintlock, and caplock).
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Single-shot actions operate only to ignite a cartridge that is separately set up ("in battery") for firing, and are incapable of moving the cartridge, itself.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] As the name implies, all single-shot firearms (unless they are multi-barreled) can only hold one round of ammunition and need to be manually reloaded after every firing.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Historically, these are the earliest cartridge firearm actions invented.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **dropping block** are actions wherein the breechblock lowers or "drops" into the receiver to open the breech, usually actuated by an underlever.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] There are two principal types of dropping block: the tilting block and the falling block.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In a **tilting block** or **pivoting block** action, the breechblock is hinged on a pin mounted at the rear (in contrast with tilting bolt, which is not hinged).
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] When the lever is operated, the block tilts down and forward, exposing the chamber.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The best-known pivoting block designs are the Peabody, the Peabody–Martini, and Ballard actions.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The original Peabody rifles, manufactured by the Providence Tool Company, used a manually cocked side-hammer.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Swiss gunsmith Friedrich Martini developed a pivoting block action by modifying the Peabody, which incorporated a hammerless striker that was cocked by the operating lever with the same single efficient motion that also pivoted the block.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The 1871 Martini–Henry which replaced the "trapdoor" Snider–Enfield was the standard British Army rifle of the later Victorian era, and the Martini is also a popular action for civilian rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Ballard's self-cocking tilting-block action was produced by the Marlin Firearms Company from 1875 and earned a superlative reputation among long-range "Creedmoor" target shooters.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Surviving Marlin Ballards are today highly prized by collectors, especially those mounted in the elaborate Swiss-style Schützen stocks of the day.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In a **falling block** or **sliding block** action, a solid metal breechblock "slides" vertically in grooves cut into the breech of the firearm and actuated by a lever.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Examples of firearms using the falling-block action are the Sharps rifle and Ruger No.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In a **rolling block** action, the breechblock takes the form of a part-cylinder, with a pivot pin through its axis.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The operator rotates or "rolls" the block to open and close the breech; it is a simple, rugged, and reliable design.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Rolling blocks are most often associated with firearms made by Remington in the late 19th century; in the Remington action the hammer serves to lock the breech closed at the moment of firing, and the block in turn prevents the hammer from falling with the breech open.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **hinged block** used in the earliest metallic-cartridge breechloaders designed for general military issue began as conversions of muzzle-loading rifle-muskets.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The upper rear portion of the barrel was filed or milled away and replaced by a hinged breechblock, which opened upward to permit loading.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] An internal angled firing pin allowed the re-use of the rifle's existing side-hammer.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The Allin action made by Springfield Arsenal in the US hinged forward; the Snider–Enfield used by the British opened to the side.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] A **break action** is a type of firearm where the barrel(s) are hinged and can be "broken open" to expose the breech.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Multi-barrel break action firearms are usually subdivided into over-and-under or side-by-side configurations for two barrel configurations or "combination gun" when mixed rifle and shotgun barrels are used.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In **bolt-action** firearms, the opening and closing of the breech is operated by direct manual manipulation of the bolt via a protruding bolt handle.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The first general-issue military breechloader was a single-shot bolt action: the paper-cartridge Prussian needle gun of 1841.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] France countered in 1866 with its superior Chassepot rifle, also a paper-cartridge bolt action.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The first metallic-cartridge bolt actions in general military service were the Berdan Type II introduced by Russia in 1870, the Mauser Model 1871, and a modified Chassepot, the Gras rifle of 1874; all these were single-shots.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Single-shot bolt actions in .22 caliber were also widely manufactured as inexpensive "boys' guns" in the earlier 20th century; and there have been a few single-shot bolt-action shotguns, usually in .410 bore.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Today, most top-level smallbore match rifles are single-shot bolt action rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **eccentric screw** action first seen on the M1867 Werndl–Holub and later on the Magnum Research Lone Eagle pistol, the breech closure is a rotating drum with the same axis, but offset from the bore.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] When locked, a firing pin aligns with the primer, the breech is otherwise solid.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] When rotated open, a slot in the drum is exposed for extraction and feeding of a new round.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Though first used on the Werndl-Holub, this action is commonly known as a cannon breech due to its association with the French 75mm Model of 1897 cannon.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The French M1897 was, itself, based on William Hubbell's U.S. patent 149,478.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] A **revolver** is a multi-chamber (but single-barrelled) firearm that houses cartridges in a rotary cylinder which indexes each round into alignment with the bore (with the help of a forcing cone) prior to each shot.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Revolvers are most often handguns; however, examples of revolving rifles, shotguns, and cannons have been made.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The cylinder is most often rotated via linkage to a manually manipulated external hammer, although some revolvers are "double-action" and can use the manual pull of the trigger to drive both the cylinder rotation and hammer cocking.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Some examples of firearms using the revolver principle are the Smith & Wesson Model 3 and Colt Model 1889.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Most bolt-actions utilize a rotating bolt ("turn-pull") design, where the bolt handle must be rotated upwards for unlocking before the bolt can be pulled back to opening the breech and eject any spent cartridge, and must be rotated back down for locking after the bolt closes the breech.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The three predominant rotating bolt-action systems are the Mauser, Lee–Enfield, and Mosin–Nagant systems, with the Mauser system emerging into the mainstream as the most widely used rotating bolt-action design.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] There are also straight pull bolt-action systems that use complex bolt head designs to facilitate locking instead of needing to rotate the bolt handle every time.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In the Mauser-style turn-bolt action, the bolt handle must be rotated upward, pull rearward, pushed forward, and finally rotated back downward into lock.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In a straight pull bolt-action, the bolt can be cycled without rotating, hence reducing the required range of motion by the shooter from four movements to two, with the goal of increasing the rate of fire.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The Ross and Schmidt–Rubin rifles load via stripper clips, albeit of an unusual paperboard and steel design in the Schmidt–Rubin rifle, while the Mannlicher uses en-bloc clips.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The Schmidt–Rubin series, which culminated in the K31, are also known for being among the most accurate military service rifles ever made.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Yet another variant of the straight pull bolt-action, of which the M1895 Lee Navy is an example, is a camming action in which pulling the bolt handle causes the bolt to rock, freeing a stud from the receiver and unlocking the bolt.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In 1993, the German firearms company Blaser, introduced the Blaser R93, a new straight pull bolt-action rifle where locking is achieved by a series of concentric "claws" that protrude/retract from the bolthead, a design that is referred to as *Radialbundverschluss* ("radial connection").
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] As of 2017 the Rifle Shooter magazine listed its successor Blaser R8 as one of the three most popular straight pull bolt-action together with Merkel Helix and Browning Maral.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Some other notable modern straight pull bolt-action rifles are made by Chapuis, Heym, Lynx, Rößler, Strasser, and Steel Action.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In the sport of biathlon, because shooting speed is an important performance factor and semi-automatic guns are illegal for race use, straight pull bolt-actions are quite common, and are used almost exclusively on the Biathlon World Cup.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The first company to make straight pull bolt-actions for .22 caliber was J.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Anschütz; the action is specifically the straight-pull ball bearing-lock action, which features spring-loaded ball bearings on the side of the bolt which lock into a groove inside the bolt's housing.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] With the new design came a new dry-fire method; instead of the bolt being turned up slightly, the action is locked back to catch the firing pin.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In **pump-action** firearms, a sliding grip at the fore-end beneath the barrel is manually operated by the user to eject and chamber cartridges.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Pump actions are predominantly found in shotguns.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Some examples of firearms using the pump-action are the Winchester Model 1912, Remington 870, and Mossberg 500.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **lever-action** firearms, a linked lever is manually operated to eject and chamber cartridges.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Some examples of firearms using lever-action are the Henry Model 1860, Winchester Model 1876, and Marlin Model 1894.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **bolt release** or **lever release** action is a hybrid repeating action that uses the physical manipulation of a bolt release lever/button to complete the cartridge chambering process.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] However, after moving rearwards the bolt is stopped by a bolt catch and will not move back into battery position and chamber the new round, until the user manually disengages the catch by depressing a release lever/button.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Due to the fact that the action can not complete its loading cycle without manual input from the user, it is technically a manually operated action rather than a self-loading one.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In 2020, CZ also introduced CZ 515, a bolt-release modified version of the CZ 512, to the Australian market via its importer Winchester Australia.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The Turkish manufacturer Pardus Arms also produces the 12 gauge-caliber BRS17 shotgun, which uses a bolt release button on the back of the receiver to chamber rounds before firing.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **blowback operation** is a system in which semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms operate through the energy created by combustion in the chamber and bore acting directly on the bolt face through the cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In blowback operation the bolt is not locked to the chamber, relying only on spring pressure and inertia from the weight of the bolt to keep the action from opening too quickly.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Blowback operation is used for low-powered cartridges due to the weight of the bolt required.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Delayed blowback actions use some mechanism to slow down rearward travel of the bolt, allowing this action to handle more powerful ammunition and/or reduced weight of the bolt.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **blow-forward** operation uses a fixed breech and moving barrel that is forced forward relative to the breech by the friction of the projectile against the bore as well as the breech recoiling away from the barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The barrel is spring loaded and returns automatically to chamber a fresh round from the magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] Examples of this action are the Steyr Mannlicher M1894, Hino Komuro M1908 Pistol and the Schwarzlose Model 1908.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **recoil operation** is a type of locked-breech action used in semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] It also uses energy from the combustion in the chamber acting directly on the bolt through the cartridge head, but in this case the firearm has a reciprocating barrel and breech assembly, combined with a bolt that locks to the breech.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The breech remains locked as the bolt and barrel travel rearward together for some distance, allowing pressure in the chamber to drop to a safe level before the breech is opened.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] The **gas operation** is a system of operation mechanism used to provide energy to semi-automatic and fully automatic firearms.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] In gas-operation, a portion of high pressure gas from the cartridge being fired is tapped through a hole in the barrel and diverted to operate the action.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] A fourth type, now considered obsolete and ineffective, are those systems based on the Bang rifle that utilize a muzzle cap to capture gas after the bullet has left the barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/action-firearms] While this system is successful in boosting the operating power of recoil operated guns, it is insufficient and too susceptible to fouling for use as the primary operating system.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] An **active shooter** is the perpetrator of an ongoing mass shooting.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The term is primarily used to characterize shooters who are targeting victims indiscriminately and at a large scale, who oftentimes, will either commit suicide or intend to be killed by police.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] More generally, an active perpetrator of a mass murder may be referred to as an **active killer**.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Most incidents occur at locations in which the killers find little impediment in pressing their attack.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Locations are generally described as *soft targets*, that is, they carry limited security measures to protect members of the public.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] In most instances, shooters die by suicide, are shot by police, or surrender when confrontation with responding law enforcement becomes unavoidable, and active shooter events are often over in 10 to 15 minutes.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The Federal Bureau of Investigation defines an active shooter as "one or more individuals actively engaged in killing or attempting to kill people in a populated area.", excluding self-defense, gang or drug violence, crossfire, and domestic disputes.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The terminology "active shooter" is critiqued by some academics.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Ron Borsch recommends the term *rapid mass murder*.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] In police training manuals, the police response to an active shooter scenario is different from hostage rescue and barricaded suspect situations.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Police officers responding to an armed barricaded suspect often deploy with the intention of containing the suspect within a perimeter, gaining information about the situation, attempting negotiation with the suspect, and waiting for specialist teams like SWAT.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] If police officers believe that a shooter intends to kill as many people as possible before killing themselves, they may use a tactic like immediate action rapid deployment.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] In the United States, the Investigative Assistance for Violent Crimes Act of 2012, passed in the aftermath of the Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting in Newtown, Connecticut, clarified the statutory authority for federal law enforcement agencies to provide investigatory assistance to the States.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] In contrast with the definitions of mass killings or mass murder, the definition of active shooter includes the use of firearms, but does not include a threshold for fatalities (which may be none).
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The scope of this program is explicitly not mass killings or mass shootings but rather "a study of a specific type of shooting situation law enforcement and the public may face." Gang- and drug-related incidents are out of scope of this initiative.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The first FBI report on active shooter incidents was published in September 2014; the FBI has since released annual updates and a 20-year review.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The 2014 FBI report on active shooter incidents covered the period 2000 through 2013 and was the first time the United States federal government comprehensively identified and studied active shooter incidents over a significant period of time.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] 160 incidents and 486 deaths were included in the study.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The frequency and severity of active shooter incidents rose during the study period, averaging 6.4 incidents per year from 2000 through 2006 and 16.4 incidents per year from 2007 through 2013, with 366 of the 486 deaths occurring from 2007 through 2013.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] According to the 2022 FBI report, the frequency of active shooter incidents rose in 2021, with 61 incidents, up from 40 in 2020 and 30 in each of 2018 and 2019.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] 103 victims were killed and 140 wounded in the 2021 incidents (not including the perpetrators).
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] In 2021, more active shooting incidents involved multiple locations.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] All but one of the 2021 active shooters were male.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Thirty of the 61 2021 active shooters were apprehended by law enforcement, 14 were killed by law enforcement, eleven took their own lives, and four were killed by armed citizens.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] According to the 2023 FBI report, the number of casualties in active shooter incidents rose in 2022, with 100 killed and 213 injured (not including the perpetrators) in 50 incidents.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Twenty-nine of the 50 2022 active shooters were apprehended by law enforcement, seven were killed by law enforcement, two were killed by armed citizens, nine took their own lives, and three remained at large.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] According to Ron Borsch, active shooters are not inclined to negotiate, preferring to kill as many people as possible, often to gain notoriety.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Active shooters generally do not lie in wait to battle responding law enforcement officers.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Few law enforcement officers have been injured responding to active shooter incidents; fewer still have been killed.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] As noted, more often than not, when the prospect of confrontation with responding law enforcement becomes unavoidable, the active shooter commits suicide.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] And when civilians—even unarmed civilians—resist, the active shooter crumbles.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Borsch's statistical analysis recommends a tactic: aggressive action.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] For law enforcement, the tactical imperative is to respond and engage the killer without delay‍—‌the affected orthodoxy of cumbersome team formations fails to answer the rapid temporal dynamics of active shooter events and fails to grasp the nature of the threat involved.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Accounts of what factors lead to this type of incident vary.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Some contend that the motive, at least proximately, is vengeance.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Others argue that bullying breeds the problem, and sometimes the active shooter is a victim of bullying, directly or indirectly.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Still others such as Grossman and DeGaetano argue that the pervasiveness of violent imagery girding modern culture hosts the phenomenon.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Another suggestion is that a particular interpretation of the world, a conscious or subconscious ontology, accounts for the phenomenon.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Proponents of this idea argue that the active shooter lives in a world of victims and victimizers, that all are one or the other.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The ontology accommodates no room between the categories for benevolence, friendship or a mixture of good and bad.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] Their interpretation of the world may be fed by bullying or violent imagery (hence the common obsession with violent movies, books or video games), but it is the absolutist interpretation that drives them both to kill and to die.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] In *The Psychology of the Active Killer*, Daniel Modell writes that "The world conceived by the active killer is a dark dialectic of victim and victimizer.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] His impoverished ontology brooks no nuance, admits no resolution.
[src:airsoft-gun/active-shooter] The two categories, isolated and absolute, exhaust and explain his world.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Depending on the mechanism for pellet propulsion, airsoft guns fall into two broad groups just like conventional airguns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] One group is spring-piston guns, which utilize elastic energy of a coil spring to propel piston air pump that is either manually cocked (i.e.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] "spring guns", commonly referred to as "*springers*", and are the simplest, cheapest and generally of low quality); or automatically cycled by a battery-powered electric motor gearbox (i.e.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] "gas guns"), which operate by bash valve-controlled pressure release of prefilled bottled gas such as compressed propane mixed with silicone oil (commonly known as "Green Gas") or CO2 canisters (Powerlets.).
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Pneumatic guns can be cycled either manually by hand-pulling back the bolt or slide, which loads the subsequent shot; or automatically by having the released propellant gas also pushing back the action (i.e.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns are often designed to aesthetically resemble real firearms, which provides more realism but also makes it difficult to distinguish them from actual lethal weapons.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft in the past was used almost solely for recreational purposes, but in 2012, gas blowback (GBB) airsoft technology became adopted by US federal and state institutions as an affordable and reliable tactical training tool for close quarters battles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In 2018, the United States Coast Guard officially adopted SIG-branded P229 airsoft pistol for training.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns also allow basic and advanced shooter training in a safer environment by reducing the risks of accidental injury or death from a negligent discharge.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] There are clubs, teams, and even athletic associations devoted to airsoft events around the world.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Europe is home to some of the largest events, with skirmishes of over 2,000 people participating.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In North America, in 2012 alone, Fulda Gap Airsoft Game in Taylorsville, North Carolina had over 1,100 participants, and Operation Lion Claws Military Simulation Series (OLCMSS) had 800 people attend at George Air Force Base in Victorville, California.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] American Mil-sim, Black Sheep, and Ballahack also host large games.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Events may include a variety of equipment ranging from small arms to armored vehicles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In many countries, every airsoft gun owner and active enthusiast must be affiliated with an accredited airsoft association or federation.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Most airsoft players host games at a registered field where combat situations are simulated using airsoft weaponry like replica pistols, submachine guns, carbines/assault rifles, DMRs/sniper rifles, light machine guns, grenades and landmines.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Great variety and profusion of militaria is usually used.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Historical reenactment of famous war situations is another favorite of many airsoft players and clubs.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In addition, a number of companies such as Systema Engineering and Celsius Technology manufacture ultra-realistic high-velocity airsoft rifles designed specifically for the police and military for non-lethal training purposes.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] People today may also use airsoft guns as props for film making, particularly after the *Rust* shooting incident.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] An Airsoft Two-Tone Gun is an Airsoft replica which has been sprayed over 51% a bright, non military colour, so that it complies with the Violent Crimes Reduction Act (VCRA, 2006), allowing anyone to buy a replica without having to prove that they have a legitimate use for it.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Spring guns are generally inexpensive (except the high-power sniper rifles and shotguns), and may not last long (depending on the build quality) due to the tension exerted on the gun parts by the recoiling of a powerful spring.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, many spring guns can be modified and upgraded to last longer and shoot more powerfully.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Low-end spring guns tend to be much cheaper than their electric equivalents due to their lack of electrical components (electric motor/actuator, spring-gearbox assembly, battery and battery charger).
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] These guns are less common in competitions because their rate-of-fire is a disadvantage against automatic guns in close combat, and they do not provide enough accuracy and power for long-range use.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] There are some exceptions, however, as higher-end spring-powered airsoft rifles can be quite expensive; these guns are typically suited for "marksman" applications in airsoft matches and provide competitive muzzle velocities.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Additionally, pump shotguns are sometimes used for both short and long range engagements.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In colder weather, spring pistols are more reliable than gas-powered pistols and even the batteries on automatic electric pistols (AEPs) both of which can be adversely affected by extremely low temperatures.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] This represents one of the major advantages of spring airsoft gun, as it can be fired in practically any situation without relying on batteries or bottled gas.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] This independence from external power sources causes some players to favor spring-powered guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Spring guns are also less susceptible to the effects of water, where a battery-powered gun could short-circuit and malfunction when wet.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Because of their low price, availability, and simplicity, spring guns tend to act as training guns for new players.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In the UK, they are affectionately known as "springers" and were often a player's introduction to the sport due to the entry-level cost in comparison to AEG and GBB weapons.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some veteran airsoft players still rely on sniper rifle and shotgun-type spring guns as a primary weapon due to reliability, high power, accuracy, low noise, and ease of repair compared to AEGs and GBB guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Selective fire options among automatic, 3-round burst and semi-automatic operations are all possible, which gives these guns the popular name "**automatic electric guns**", or **AEGs**.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They are the most commonly used and widely available type of airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] AEGs were developed in Japan and the Japanese company Tokyo Marui is credited with creating the original gearbox system.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In a Tokyo Marui AEG, the motor drives a train of three gears mounted inside a gearbox, which then loads a pump piston against a spring.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Once the spring is released, it pushes the piston plunger forward through the pump cylinder to propel a pellet resting within the chamber forward through the barrel and out of the muzzle.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Many manufacturers have now more or less replicated this basic model, adding reinforced parts or minor improvements.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The electric airsoft guns were powered primarily by nickel-metal hydride (NiMH) batteries with varying voltages and milliampere-hour ratings.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common battery is an 8.4 V large battery pack, with a capacity between 2200 and 5000 mAh.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Also available are "mini" and "stick" batteries, which generally have 900 ~ 1600 mAh capacities.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Voltages for NiMH batteries range from 7.2 V to 12 V.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The usual rule of thumb is that the higher the mAh rating, the longer the battery lasts; the higher the voltage, the higher the rate of fire.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common AEGs are the AR-15 series (such as M16 rifle and M4 carbine, sometimes referred to as the ArmaLite or Colt series), the H&K MP5 series, and the AK or Kalashnikov series.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Also increasingly popular is the H&K G36 and, more recently, the FN P90 and H&K MP7.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Subsequently, numerous parts for repairs and modifications are commonly available for these rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some airsoft guns are called *low-powered electric guns* (LPEGs) to distinguish them from the original, more expensive and more powerful AEGs even though their mechanical/electrical design and operation is similar.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] MPEGs are the middle ground between LPEGs and AEGs.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some companies, like UTG with their popular MP5 and AK-47 models, have improved their quality to such an extent that some models are now considered more affordable AEGs.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Electric blowbacks, also known as EBBs, are typically available at lower prices than their battery-powered counterparts.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They generally run on AAA or AA batteries.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Most models utilizing this system are rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] EBBs simulate the blowback action of a real pistol or rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Essentially an AEG in design, EBBs are just as powerful.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, a drawback to having the realistic recoil feature is the tendency of the battery to quickly deplete.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Additionally, blowbacks can cause extra stress on the gear box which may result in a shorter life span.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Automatic electric pistols, abbreviated AEPs, were first introduced by Tokyo Marui in 2005 with their Glock 18C (followed later by a Beretta 93R model).
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They were the first handguns to incorporate an electrically powered system that is capable of fully automatic operation.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In cold weather, AEPs are often considered better sidearms than gas powered pistols, because batteries are not as badly affected by frigid weather.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Gases like CO2 and green gas are stored in liquid form and require heat in order to vaporize.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] A gas pistol at 10 °F (−12 °C) will usually only get one to two usable shots from a full magazine, and even will be at reduced power because of the lowered pressure of the gas.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Because the AEP gearbox and battery are smaller, the velocity of AEP BBs (usually between 200 and 280 ft/s (85.3 m/s)) is relatively slow by the standards of airsoft simulations, rendering them useful only for close-range simulation.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, the advanced hop up units on these new guns tend to compensate for the low power and can produce an effective range comparable to those of an AEG.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] CYMA has made a clone Glock 18C, which is a lower priced alternative.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] An AEP differs from electric blow-backs because the AEP has a fixed slide (in which there is no external movement of the slide during operation), while an EBB simulates the "blow back" action in the slide experienced in a real pistol or Gas Blow Back (GBB).
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] An AEP, however, has much more power and accuracy.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] One of the newer AEP-styled guns is the Marui replica of the Heckler & Koch MP7.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] It is considerably larger than either of the other guns, and can be upgraded to a much higher power through the use of an external battery, but uses the same system as the AEP, so the classification is ambiguous.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] It is slightly more powerful than the others and is a suitable choice for CQB (Close Quarter Battle) games due to its small size and decent barrel- to gun-length ratio.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some semi-automatic pistols can be modified to be automatic pistols.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] To make them more effective, they use rechargeable batteries supplied with the gun, which can be replaced with a larger battery to increase their ROF.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Due to restrictions on size, either the electric motor or batteries have to occupy space in the hand grip, reducing the available space for a magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Because of this, most AEPs do not use a full size magazine found in most gas powered pistols.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They are typically constructed almost entirely of plastic and have a light, toy-like feeling to them.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Gas-powered airsoft guns use the pneumatic potential energy stored within compressed gas to drive the shooting mechanism, and thus operate according to an entirely different design principle to spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common type seen is the gas blowback (GBB) guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] These gas guns use an internal canister (usually within the magazine) that upon trigger-pull releases the prefilled bottled gas via a series of valves to propel the pellet and generate a blowback, which simulates recoil and cyclically loads the next shot.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They are capable of both automatic and semi-automatic operation.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common gases used are "green gas" and propane which requires an adaptor.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] HFC-134a is also commonly used, particularly with pistols which have plastic sliders due to the lower pressure giving a smaller chance of damage to the weaker slide.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Less commonly used gases include "red gas" (which is actually HCFC-22), CO2 and nitrogen/high-pressure air.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, it is unlawful to use HCFC-22 as a propellant in the US, as it is a Class II ozone-depleting substance and its use as an aerosol propellant has been banned since January 1994 under section 610(d) of Clean Air Act.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Red gas is usually avoided unless the airsoft gun has undergone modification, as its relatively high critical pressure can cause damage to the airsoft gun, such as breakage of the slide or bolt.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] CO2, nitrogen, and high pressure air are less common because they need to be stored at higher pressures than "green gas" or HFC-134a.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The first ever gas powered airsoft guns were commonly referred to as "classic" guns, owing to their age.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] R-12 was a commonly used refrigerant for car air conditioning and refrigerators, and is considered a highly potent ozone-depleting substance and listed as a Class I Ozone Depleting Substance by the US EPA.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Its use as a general purpose aerosol propellant has been banned by the US EPA since March 1978 under 43 FR 11301 for use in aerosol use with a very few exceptions.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Its use is also banned in many countries under United Nations treaties.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] On December 31, 2008, the use of CFCs for medical inhalers was banned.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Later users modified these old guns to be powered by regulated CO2 canisters or nitrogen/high pressure air bottles to increase power and consistency.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, these guns have largely been superseded by the newer and more versatile AEGs, or automatic electric guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] One of the reasons for this is because the most commonly available propellant, R-12, is costly.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Additionally, at high flow rates, liquid propellants tend to cool down, eventually freezing.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] As cooldown progresses, the rate of fire gradually decreases until the gun ceases operation.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The user would then be forced to wait for the propellant to warm up again.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] CO2 is not affected as badly by this tendency, and nitrogen/high pressure air is immune to it.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Furthermore, if liquid propellant is introduced into the gun's mechanism, rubber parts can freeze and eventually damage the gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, it is unlikely for this to occur since once the gas is released from the containing cylinder it instantly turns back into its gaseous state, and expands rapidly.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] It is doubtful whether the retained pressure behind the BB before it begins to accelerate down the barrel is enough to keep the gas in a liquid form.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Also, any gun that is expected to be exposed to the intense cold of de-pressurizing gas should have materials that can handle it.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Gas power tends to be used in airsoft pistols where size constraints make electric-powered mechanisms impractical.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Other instances where gas is favored are where adjustable velocities are required or where a blowback feature is desired.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] A blowback feature is a mechanism which cycles a slide or bolt to better simulate a real firearm's operation.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Because of the mechanical complexities involved with distributing and regulating gas, these guns have largely given way to electric guns for less specialized applications, however, they still remain favorable amongst most airsofters.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They are not just limited to pistols; submachine guns, sniper rifles and assault rifles commonly use gas mechanisms.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Whilst the submachine gun replicas typically feature a blowback mechanism similar to the pistol replicas, sniper rifle replicas usually omit the blowback mechanism in favor of reduced recoil and increased muzzle velocity.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Along with using gas to power guns, it is also applied for use in replica grenades.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] These grenades are either projectiles, fired from a grenade launcher such as the M203 or GP-25, or throwable.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The shells work on the system of an internal piston, filled with gas.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Either a series of BB's or in some cases a rubber or soft foam head is seated in or on top of the shell.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] When the pressure is released the projectile(s) are shot from the launcher sent downrange.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In the case of the throwable grenades, inside the grenade there is a similar piston to the one used in the shells, but is on a literal "timer" that allows the user to clear the area of effect.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] BBs or powder acts as the projectile in the case of these grenades.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Currently both types of grenades are not very common, mostly because grenade launchers are quite expensive and the throwable grenades are not very reliable.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] High pressure air (HPA) systems are a type of pneumatic airsoft weapon that use externally supplied high pressure air instead of internal gas canisters like the majority of gas-operated airsoft guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They work by using a separate high-pressure air tank that is connected to the airsoft gun with a hose, which is connected with a pneumatic motor inside the gun (called an "engine") at where the gearbox would be in a normal electric airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The engine is powered by a fire control unit that can adjust to the desired rates of fire as well as the dwell that determines how much air is released with each individual shot.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft gun manufacturer Systema Engineering (PTW) developed a line of airsoft guns and accessories intended for military and law enforcement training.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] These airsoft guns are made of aircraft-grade aluminium combined with stainless steel parts that gives strength, stability, weather protection, and easy maintenance.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] These training weapons offer a more realistic display of military weapons.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Unfortunately they have been plagued by reliability problems and parts availability.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] They have also had models banned from the US for being capable of being converted into real firearms.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Two manufactures, King Arms and KWA, came out with ATF-approved gas blowback AR-15 replicas that allowed for correct weapons tear down, manipulation and function that were designed for military use, but were also legal for US citizens to own.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The King Arms model required upgrade parts out of the parts to give it reliability, though the KWA was plagued by a weak hop-up system, but otherwise reliable.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns shoot plastic pellets at velocities from 30 m/s (98 ft/s) for a low-end spring pistol, to 200 m/s (660 ft/s) for heavily upgraded customized sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Most non-upgraded AEGs are in the middle, producing velocities from 90 m/s (300 ft/s) to 120 m/s (390 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The internal components of most guns can be upgraded which can increase the pellet velocity significantly.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Using heavier pellets (.25 g, .3 g, etc.) will significantly reduce the gun's muzzle velocity, but can increase accuracy at range and reduce susceptibility to wind drift.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Lighter pellets have less kinetic energy than their heavier pellets, despite their higher exit velocity.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Decreasing the pellet's weight does not generally increase its range.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] A common upgrade done by players is in the "hop-up" system, featured in most mid- to high-end AEGs, as well as gas guns and spring sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In this system, the wall of a rubber tube, called a bucking, is forced into the upper path of the pellet right before it begins flying down the inner barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] This contact imparts backspin, which in turn gives the pellet a Magnus lift to maintain a flatter trajectory for a longer period of time.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] This is adjusted by screws or gears that cause the bucking to only show a small or large presence in the barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Different degrees of firmness of the rubber are considered when a hop-up is being upgraded.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft is safe when played with proper protective gear.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Most airsoft guns on the market are usually below 350 ft/s (110 m/s), but projectiles expelled from any type of airsoft gun can travel as slow as 65 ft/s (20 m/s) to more than 700 ft/s (210 m/s) and are capable of breaking skin at 350–400 ft/s (110–120 m/s).
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] For example, skirmish play in the United Kingdom has a maximum of 350 ft/s, with some airsoft locations having a limit as low as 290 ft/s.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] If under 300 ft/s (91 m/s), the hit would have to be within a short range.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Blood can be drawn, but injuries that do occur are predominantly superficial.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Full-seal protective eyewear (goggles or glasses) is widely considered the minimum protection for airsoft players, as the eyes may be injured by any type of impact.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The least amount of protection a player should seek will meet or exceed ANSI/ISEA Z87.1 standards, which indicates the eyewear is rated for ballistic strikes.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Mesh eyewear has also seen some limited use by players due to low cost and its inability to fog, although it has drawn some criticism for its non-impact rated construction and vulnerability to debris.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some impacts (particularly at close range with powerful guns) are capable of cracking or damaging teeth.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Dentists have reported broken teeth that require root canal and crowns to repair damage.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] A face mask (like that used for paintball) is recommended to protect eyes and teeth.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Metallic mesh masks and mouth guards have recently seen popular use.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] There are legal issues in airsoft as well as several rules imposed in a game by game basis.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Most indoor airsoft fields only allow up to 350 ft/s (110 m/s), and most outdoor fields begin capping near the 410 ft/s (125 m/s) for rifles and 525 ft/s (160 m/s) for long-range guns such as sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Most outdoor fields also impose a minimum engagement distance for guns firing over a certain range, normally for squad support weapons and sniper rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In order for an airsoft gun to cause any serious injury, it would have to be well over these limits and in close proximity.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] To even reach such speeds, the gun would have to be highly modified.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] So it is therefore unlikely to cause permanent or serious damage with any stock airsoft gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The use of metallic BBs, or any foreign objects, is very dangerous for the user and other people and property in close vicinity, and may damage the airsoft gun as well.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] However, specially designed and built metallic 6 mm BBs for airsoft guns can be found on the market.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] These metallic BBs should not be used for airsoft play because they can break through goggles and other safety gear.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Plastic BBs can be a mixture of PLA and Plastic causing less damage to persons.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Although airsoft guns in the United States are generally sold with a 6 mm (0.24in.) or longer orange tip on the barrel in order to distinguish them from real firearms, this is not in fact required by federal law.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Full or partial preventive painting of airsoft guns as a legal obligation to avoid confusion of the airsoft replicas with real lethal weapons is in practice in several jurisdictions around the world.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] A common controversy referred to as "pumping" or "roping" is the act of purposely firing 20+ airsoft rounds at one player until they run away or submit in pain.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Popular videos such as *Rip Kid* and *SC Trip 2015* have both documented the act of pumping.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] A CBS News report noted that since from 2014 to 2024, more than 300 people had been shot and killed by police while holding realistic replica guns, of which 19 were minors.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some airsoft guns can be such accurate replicas that they violate intellectual property laws (specifically those regarding trademarks), most notably some models from Tokyo Marui bearing Colt or Heckler & Koch trademarks that may not be imported into the United States.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Certain companies such as Classic Army or ICS avoid this problem by licensing their replicas from the original manufacturers, such as ArmaLite by license from ActionSportGames or Olympic Arms.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] The airsoft company ActionSportGames has licensed trademark rights from many well-known firearm manufacturers, such as Armalite, Dan Wesson, CZ, Steyr, STI, B&T and Franchi.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Another company who licence the designs of gun companies is Evolution International.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] It has a portfolio of exclusive licenses from ADC Armi Dallera Custom, TangoDown, Z-M Weapons, DSR precision, Lone Star Tactical, and SAR.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In addition, there have been reports of companies taking action in defense of their intellectual property rights.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Some end users have made attempts to sell their guns, some in the style of Glock pistols, only to find Glock blocking the sale and threatening legal action.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In addition to these actions, Glock, as well as Heckler & Koch, have blocked the sale, trade and distribution of replicas bearing resemblance to their products.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] Recently, Glock gave the licensing to the Glock name and likeness to Elite Force/Umarex to produce replica models of the real Glock series of firearms.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] In response, SIG Air, SIG Sauer's airgun division, announced on January 17, 2019, that it was introducing its own in-house ProForce airsoft line for professional training, with the initial offerings include the M17 and P229 airsoft pistol.
[src:airsoft-gun/airsoft-gun] SIG Air also announced that "we are rapidly expanding the SIG AIR business, and it is important to us to assume full control to ensure all SIG Air products are of the highest quality", and it would no longer be licensing the "SIG" brand or trademarks for sale by commercial airsoft manufacturers.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The **AK-47**, officially known as the **Avtomat Kalashnikova** (Russian: Автомат Калашникова, lit.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] 'Kalashnikov's automatic'; also known as the **Kalashnikov** or just **AK**), is an assault rifle chambered for the 7.62×39mm cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Developed in the Soviet Union by Russian small-arms designer Mikhail Kalashnikov, it is the originating firearm of the Kalashnikov (or "AK") family of rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] After more than seven decades since its creation, the AK-47 model and its variants remain one of the most popular and widely used firearms in the world.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It was presented for official military trials in 1947, and, in 1948, the fixed-stock version was introduced into active service for selected units of the Soviet Army.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In early 1949, the AK was officially accepted by the Soviet Armed Forces and used by the majority of the member states of the Warsaw Pact.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The model and its variants owe their global popularity to their reliability under harsh conditions, low production cost (compared to contemporary weapons), availability in virtually every geographic region, and ease of use.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK has been manufactured in many countries and has seen service with armed forces as well as irregular forces and insurgencies throughout the world.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] As of 2004, "of the estimated 500 million firearms worldwide, approximately 100 million belong to the Kalashnikov family, three-quarters of which are AK-47s".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The model is the basis for the development of many other types of individual, crew-served, and specialized firearms.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] During World War II, the Sturmgewehr 44 rifle used by German forces made a deep impression on their Soviet counterparts.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The select-fire rifle was chambered for a new intermediate cartridge, the 7.92×33mm Kurz, and combined the firepower of a submachine gun with the range and accuracy of a rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] On 15 July 1943, an earlier model of the Sturmgewehr was demonstrated before the People's Commissariat of Arms of the USSR.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The Soviets were impressed with the weapon and immediately set about developing an intermediate caliber fully automatic rifle of their own, to replace the PPSh-41 submachine guns and outdated Mosin–Nagant bolt-action rifles that armed most of the Soviet Army.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The Soviets soon developed the 7.62×39mm M43 cartridge, used in the semi-automatic SKS carbine and the RPD light machine gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Shortly after World War II, the Soviets developed the AK-47 rifle, which quickly replaced the SKS in Soviet service.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Introduced in 1959, the AKM is a lighter stamped steel version and the most ubiquitous variant of the entire AK series of firearms.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In the 1960s, the Soviets introduced the RPK light machine gun, an AK-type weapon with a stronger receiver, a longer heavy barrel, and a bipod, that eventually replaced the RPD light machine gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Mikhail Kalashnikov began his career as a weapon designer in 1941 while recuperating from a shoulder wound that he received during the Battle of Bryansk.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Kalashnikov himself stated..."I was in the hospital, and a soldier in the bed beside me asked: 'Why do our soldiers have only one rifle for two or three of our men when the Germans have automatics?' So I designed one.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] I was a soldier, and I created a machine gun for a soldier.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 is best described as a hybrid of previous rifle technology innovations.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] "Kalashnikov decided to design an automatic rifle combining the best features of the American M1 Garand and the German StG 44." Kalashnikov's team had access to these weapons and did not need to "reinvent the wheel".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Kalashnikov himself observed: "A lot of Russian Army soldiers ask me how one can become a constructor, and how new weaponry is designed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Each designer seems to have his own paths, his own successes and failures.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] But one thing is clear: before attempting to create something new, it is vital to have a good appreciation of everything that already exists in this field.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Some claimed that Kalashnikov copied designs like Bulkin's TKB-415 or Simonov's AVS-31.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Kalashnikov started work on a submachine gun design in 1942 and a light machine gun design in 1943.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Early in 1944, Kalashnikov was given some 7.62×39mm M43 cartridges and informed that other designers were working on weapons for this new Soviet small-arms cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It was suggested that a new weapon might well lead to greater things.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] He then undertook work on the new rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In 1944, he entered a design competition with this new 7.62×39mm, semi-automatic, gas-operated, long-stroke piston carbine, strongly influenced by the American M1 Garand.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The new rifle was in the same class as the SKS-45 carbine, with a fixed magazine and gas tube above the barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] However, the new Kalashnikov design lost out to a Simonov design.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In 1946, a new design competition was initiated to develop a new rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Kalashnikov submitted a gas-operated rifle with a short-stroke gas piston above the barrel, a breechblock mechanism similar to his 1944 carbine, and a curved 30-round magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Kalashnikov's rifles, the AK-1 (with a milled receiver) and AK-2 (with a stamped receiver) proved to be reliable weapons and were accepted to a second round of competition along with other designs.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] These prototypes (also known as the AK-46) had a rotating bolt, a two-part receiver with separate trigger unit housing, dual controls (separate safety and fire selector switches), and a non-reciprocating charging handle located on the left side of the weapon.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This design had many similarities to the StG 44(though StG 44 had closed tilting bolt).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In late 1946, as the rifles were being tested, one of Kalashnikov's assistants, Aleksandr Zaitsev, suggested a major redesign to improve reliability.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] At first, Kalashnikov was reluctant, given that their rifle had already fared better than its competitors.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Eventually, however, Zaitsev managed to persuade Kalashnikov.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In November 1947, the new prototypes (AK-47s) were completed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The rifle used a long-stroke gas piston above the barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The upper and lower receivers were combined into a single receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The selector and safety were combined into a single control lever/dust cover on the right side of the rifle and the bolt handle was attached to the bolt carrier.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This simplified the design and production of the rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The first army trial series began in early 1948.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The new rifle proved to be reliable under a wide range of conditions and possessed convenient handling characteristics.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In 1949, it was adopted by the Soviet Army as the "7.62 mm Kalashnikov rifle (AK)".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] There were many difficulties during the initial phase of production.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The first production models had stamped sheet metal receivers with a milled trunnion and butt stock insert and a stamped body.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Difficulties were encountered in welding the guide and ejector rails, causing high rejection rates.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Instead of halting production, a heavy machined receiver was substituted for the sheet metal receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Even though production of these milled rifles started in 1951, they were officially referred to as AK-49, based on the date their development started, but they are widely known in the collectors' and current commercial market as "Type 2 AK-47".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This was a more costly process, but the use of machined receivers accelerated production as tooling and labor for the earlier Mosin–Nagant rifle's machined receiver were easily adapted.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Partly because of these problems, the Soviets were not able to distribute large numbers of the new rifles to soldiers until 1956.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] During this time, production of the interim SKS rifle continued.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Once the manufacturing difficulties of non-milled receivers had been overcome, a redesigned version designated the AKM (M for "modernized" or "upgraded"; in Russian: Автомат Калашникова Модернизированный [*Avtomat Kalashnikova Modernizirovanniy*]) was introduced in 1959.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This new model used a stamped sheet metal receiver and featured a slanted muzzle brake on the end of the barrel to compensate for muzzle rise under recoil.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In addition, a hammer retarder was added to prevent the weapon from firing out of battery (without the bolt being fully closed), during rapid or fully automatic fire.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This is also sometimes referred to as a "cyclic rate reducer", or simply "rate reducer", as it also has the effect of reducing the number of rounds fired per minute during fully automatic fire.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The rifle was also roughly one-third lighter than the previous model.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Most licensed and unlicensed productions of the Kalashnikov assault rifle abroad were of the AKM variant, partially due to the much easier production of the stamped receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This model is the most commonly encountered, having been produced in much greater quantities.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] All rifles based on the Kalashnikov design are often colloquially referred to as "AK-47s" in the West and some parts of Asia, although this is only correct when applied to rifles based on the original three receiver types.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In most former Eastern Bloc countries, the weapon is known simply as the "Kalashnikov" or "AK".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The differences between the milled and stamped receivers includes the use of rivets rather than welds on the stamped receiver, as well as the placement of a small dimple above the magazine well for stabilization of the magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In 1974, the Soviets began replacing their AK-47 and AKM rifles with a newer design, the AK-74, which uses 5.45×39mm ammunition.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This new rifle and cartridge had only started to be manufactured in Eastern European nations when the Soviet Union collapsed, drastically slowing the production of the AK-74 and other weapons of the former Soviet bloc.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 was designed to be a simple, reliable fully automatic rifle that could be manufactured quickly and cheaply, using mass production methods that were state of the art in the Soviet Union during the late 1940s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 uses a long-stroke gas system generally associated with high reliability in adverse conditions.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The large gas piston, generous clearance between moving parts, and tapered cartridge case design allow the gun to endure large amounts of foreign matter and fouling without failing to cycle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK fires the 7.62×39mm cartridge with a muzzle velocity of 715 m/s (2,350 ft/s).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The cartridge weight is 16.3 g (0.6 oz), and the projectile weight is 7.9 g (122 gr).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The original Soviet M43 bullets are 123-grain boat-tail bullets with a copper-plated steel jacket, a large steel core, and some lead between the core and the jacket.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK has excellent penetration when shooting through heavy foliage, walls, or a common vehicle's metal body and into an opponent attempting to use these things as cover.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The 7.62×39mm M43 projectile does not generally fragment when striking an opponent and has an unusual tendency to remain intact even after making contact with bone.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The 7.62×39mm round produces significant wounding in cases where the bullet tumbles (yaws) in tissue, but produces relatively minor wounds in cases where the bullet exits before beginning to yaw.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In the absence of yaw, the M43 round can pencil through tissue with relatively little injury.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Most, if not all, of the 7.62×39mm ammunition found today is of the upgraded M67 variety.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This variety deleted the steel insert, shifting the center of gravity rearward, and allowing the projectile to destabilize (or yaw) at about 3.3 in (8.4 cm), nearly 6.7 in (17 cm) earlier in tissue than the M43 round.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This change also reduces penetration in ballistic gelatin to ~25 in (64 cm) for the newer M67 round versus ~29 in (74 cm) for the older M43 round.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] However, the wounding potential of M67 is mostly limited to the small permanent wound channel the bullet itself makes, especially when the bullet yaws.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] To fire, the operator inserts a loaded magazine, pulls back and releases the charging handle, and then pulls the trigger.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In semi-automatic, the firearm fires only once, requiring the trigger to be released and depressed again for the next shot.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In fully automatic, the rifle continues to fire automatically cycling fresh rounds into the chamber until the magazine is exhausted or pressure is released from the trigger.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] After ignition of the cartridge primer and propellant, rapidly expanding propellant gases are diverted into the gas cylinder above the barrel through a vent near the muzzle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The moving assembly has about 5.5 mm (0.2 in) of free travel, which creates a delay between the initial recoil impulse of the piston and the bolt unlocking sequence, allowing gas pressures to drop to a safe level before the seal between the chamber and the bolt is broken.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 does not have a gas valve; excess gases are ventilated through a series of radial ports in the gas cylinder.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The Kalashnikov platform then uses an extractor claw along with a fin shaped ejector to eject the spent cartridge case.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The rifle received a barrel with a chrome-lined bore and four right-hand grooves at a 240 mm (1 in 9.45 in) or 31.5 calibers rifling twist rate.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The gas block contains a gas channel that is installed at a slanted angle with the bore axis.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The muzzle is threaded for the installation of various muzzle devices such as a muzzle brake or a blank-firing adaptor.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The gas block of the AK-47 features a cleaning rod capture or sling loop.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Gas relief ports that alleviate gas pressure are placed horizontally in a row on the gas cylinder.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The fire selector is a large lever located on the right side of the rifle; it acts as a dust cover and prevents the charging handle from being pulled fully to the rear when it is on safe.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It is operated by the shooter's right fore-fingers and has three settings: safe (up), full-auto (center), and semi-auto (down).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The reason for this is that a soldier under stress will push the selector lever down with considerable force, bypassing the full-auto stage and setting the rifle to semi-auto.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] To set the AK-47 to full-auto requires the deliberate action of centering the selector lever.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] To operate the fire selector lever, right-handed shooters have to briefly remove their right hand from the pistol grip, which is ergonomically sub-optimal.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Some AK-type rifles also have a more traditional selector lever on the left side of the receiver, just above the pistol grip.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This lever is operated by the shooter's right thumb and has three settings: safe (forward), full-auto (center), and semi-auto (backward).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 uses a notched rear tangent iron sight calibrated in 100 m (109 yd) increments from 100 to 800 m (109 to 875 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The front sight is a post adjustable for elevation in the field.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Horizontal adjustment requires a special drift tool and is done by the armory before the issue or if the need arises by an armorer after the issue.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The sight line elements are approximately 48.5 mm (1.9 in) over the bore axis.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The "point-blank range" battle zero setting 'П', standing for постоянная (*postoyannaya*, 'constant') on the 7.62×39mm AK-47 rear tangent sight element corresponds to a 300 m (328 yd) zero.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] These settings mirror the Mosin–Nagant and SKS rifles, which the AK-47 replaced.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] For the AK-47 combined with service cartridges, the 300 m battle zero setting limits the apparent "bullet rise" within approximately −5 to +31 cm (−2.0 to 12.2 in) relative to the line of sight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Soldiers are instructed to fire at any target within this range by simply placing the sights on the center of mass (the belt buckle, according to Russian and former Soviet doctrine) of the enemy target.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Any errors in range estimation are tactically irrelevant, as a well-aimed shot will hit the torso of the enemy soldier.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Some AK-type rifles have a front sight with a flip-up luminous dot that is calibrated at 50 m (55 yd), for improved night fighting.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 was originally equipped with a buttstock, handguard, and an upper heat guard made from solid wood.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] With the introduction of the Type 3 receiver the buttstock, lower handguard, and upper heat guard were manufactured from birch plywood laminates.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Such engineered woods are stronger and resist warping better than the conventional one-piece patterns, do not require lengthy maturing, and are cheaper.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The wooden furniture was finished with the Russian amber shellac finishing process.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] AKS and AKMS models featured a downward-folding metal butt-stock similar to that of the German MP40 submachine-gun, for use in the restricted space in the BMP infantry combat vehicle, as well as by paratroops.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] All 100 series AKs use plastic furniture with side-folding stocks.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The standard magazine capacity is 30 rounds.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] There are also 10-, 20-, and 40-round box magazines, as well as 75-round drum magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47's standard 30-round magazines have a pronounced curve that allows them to smoothly feed ammunition into the chamber.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Their heavy steel construction combined with "feed-lips" (the surfaces at the top of the magazine that control the angle at which the cartridge enters the chamber) machined from a single steel billet makes them highly resistant to damage.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] These magazines are so strong that "Soldiers have been known to use their mags as hammers, and even bottle openers".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This contributes to the AK-47 magazine being more reliable but makes it heavier than US and NATO magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The early slab-sided steel AK-47 30-round detachable box magazines had 1 mm (0.039 in) sheet-metal bodies and weighed 430 g (0.95 lb) empty.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The later steel AKM 30-round magazines had lighter sheet-metal bodies with prominent reinforcing ribs weighing 0.33 kg (0.73 lb) empty.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] To further reduce weight, a lightweight magazine with an aluminum body with a prominent reinforcing waffle rib pattern weighing 0.19 kg (0.42 lb) empty was developed for the AKM that proved to be too fragile, and the small issued amount of these magazines were quickly withdrawn from service.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] As a replacement, steel-reinforced 30-round plastic 7.62×39mm box magazines were introduced.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Noted for their durability, these magazines did however compromise the rifle's camouflage and lacked the small horizontal reinforcing ribs running down both sides of the magazine body near the front that were added on all later plastic magazine generations.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] A second-generation steel-reinforced dark-brown (color shades vary from maroon to plum to near black) 30-round 7.62×39mm magazine was introduced in the early 1980s, fabricated from ABS plastic.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The third generation steel-reinforced 30-round 7.62×39mm magazine is similar to the second generation, but is darker colored and has a matte non-reflective surface finish.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The current issue is a steel-reinforced matte true black non- reflective surface finished 7.62×39mm 30-round magazine, fabricated from ABS plastic weighing 0.25 kg (0.55 lb) empty.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Early steel AK-47 magazines are 9.75 in (248 mm) long; the later ribbed steel AKM and newer plastic 7.62×39mm magazines are about 1 in (25 mm) shorter.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The transition from steel to mainly plastic magazines yields a significant weight reduction and allows a soldier to carry more ammunition for the same weight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] All 7.62×39mm AK magazines are backward compatible with older AK variants.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] 10.12 kg (22.3 lb) is the maximum amount of ammo that the average soldier can comfortably carry.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It also allows for the best comparison of the three most common 7.62×39mm AK magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Most Yugoslavian magazines were made with cartridge followers that hold the bolt open when empty.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Accessories supplied with the rifle include a 387 mm (15.2 in) long 6H3 bayonet featuring a 200 mm (7.9 in) long spear point blade.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 bayonet is installed by slipping the 17.7 mm (0.70 in) diameter muzzle ring around the muzzle and latching the handle down on the bayonet lug under the front sight base.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] All current model AKM rifles can mount under-barrel 40 mm grenade launchers such as the GP-25 and its variants, which can fire up to 20 rounds per minute and have an effective range of up to 400 meters.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The main grenade is the VOG-25 (VOG-25M) fragmentation grenade which has a 6 m (9 m) (20 ft (30 ft)) lethality radius.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 can also mount a (rarely used) cup-type grenade launcher, the Kalashnikov grenade launcher that fires standard RGD-5 Soviet hand grenades.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The maximum effective range is approximately 150 meters.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This launcher can also be used to launch tear gas and riot control grenades.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] All current AKs (100 series) and some older models have side rails for mounting a variety of scopes and sighting devices, such as the PSO-1 Optical Sniper Sight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The side rails allow for the removal and remounting of optical accessories without interfering with the zeroing of the optic.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] However, the 100 series side folding stocks cannot be folded with the optics mounted.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 and its variants have been and are made in dozens of countries, with "quality ranging from finely engineered weapons to pieces of questionable workmanship." As a result, the AK-47 has a service/system life of approximately 6,000 to 15,000 rounds.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 was designed to be a cheap, simple, easy-to-manufacture rifle, perfectly matching Soviet military doctrine that treats equipment and weapons as disposable items.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] As units are often deployed without adequate logistical support and dependent on "battlefield cannibalization" for resupply, it is more cost-effective to replace rather than repair weapons.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 has small parts and springs that need to be replaced every few thousand rounds.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] However, "Every time it is disassembled beyond the field stripping stage, it will take some time for some parts to regain their fit, and some parts may tend to shake loose and fall out when firing the weapon.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Some parts of the AK-47 line are riveted together.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] According to the Kalashnikov Concern company (formerly Izhmash), most foreign-made AK-type rifles are unlicensed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47's accuracy is generally sufficient to hit an adult male torso out to about 300 m (328 yd), though even experts firing from prone or bench rest positions at this range were observed to have difficulty placing ten consecutive rounds on target.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Later designs did not significantly improve the rifle's accuracy.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The best shooters can hit a man-sized target at 800 m (875 yd) within five shots (firing from a prone or bench rest position) or ten shots (standing).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Under worst field exercise circumstances, the hit probabilities for all the tested rifles were drastically reduced, from 34% at 50m down to 3–4% at 600m with no significant differences between weapons at each range.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The following table represents the Russian circular error probable method for determining accuracy, which involves drawing two circles on the target, one for the maximum vertical dispersion of hits and one for the maximum horizontal dispersion of hits.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] They then disregard the hits on the outer part of the target and only count half of the hits (50% or R50) on the inner part of the circles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This significantly reduces the overall diameter of the groups.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] They then use both the vertical and horizontal measurements of the reduced groups to measure accuracy.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] When the R50 results are doubled, the hit probability increases to 93.7%.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The vertical and horizontal mean (R50) deviations with service ammunition at 800 m (875 yd) for AK platforms are.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Throughout the world, the AK and its variants are commonly used by governments, revolutionaries, terrorists, criminals, and civilians alike.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In some countries, such as Somalia, Rwanda, Mozambique, Congo, and Tanzania, black market prices for AKs are between $30 and $125 per weapon and prices have fallen in the last few decades due to mass counterfeiting.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In Kenya, "an AK-47 fetches five head of cattle (about 10,000 Kenya shillings or 100 US dollars) when offered for barter, but costs almost half that price when cash is paid".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] There are places around the world where AK-type weapons can be purchased on the black market "for as little as $6, or traded for a chicken or a sack of grain".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 has also spawned a cottage industry of sorts and has been copied and manufactured (one gun at a time) in small shops around the world (see Khyber Pass Copy).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The estimated numbers of AK-type weapons vary greatly.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The Small Arms Survey suggests that "between 70 and 100 million of these weapons have been produced since 1947".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The World Bank estimates that out of the 500 million total firearms available worldwide, 100 million are of the Kalashnikov family, and 75 million are AK-47s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Because AK-type weapons have been made in many countries, often illicitly, it is impossible to know how many exist.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] During the Cold War, the Soviet Union and the People's Republic of China, as well as United States and other NATO nations supplied arms and technical knowledge to numerous countries and rebel forces around the world.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] During this time the Western countries used relatively expensive automatic rifles, such as the FN FAL, the HK G3, the M14, and the M16.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In contrast, the Russians and Chinese used the AK-47; its low production cost and ease of manufacture allow them to make AKs in vast numbers.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In the pro-communist states, the AK-47 became a symbol of the Third World revolution.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] They were utilized in the Cambodian Civil War and the Cambodian–Vietnamese War.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] During the 1980s, the Soviet Union became the principal arms dealer to countries embargoed by Western nations, including Middle Eastern nations such as Libya and Syria, which welcomed Soviet Union backing against Israel.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In Russia, the Kalashnikov is a tremendous source of national pride.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] There are also Kalashnikov watches, umbrellas, and knives.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The Kalashnikov Museum (also called the AK-47 museum) opened on 4 November 2004 in Izhevsk, Udmurt Republic.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] This city is in the Ural Region of Russia.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The museum chronicles the biography of General Kalashnikov and documents the invention of the AK-47.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The museum complex of Kalashnikov's small arms, a series of halls, and multimedia exhibitions are devoted to the evolution of the AK-47 rifle and attracts 10,000 monthly visitors.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Nadezhda Vechtomova, the museum director, stated in an interview that the purpose of the museum is to honor the ingenuity of the inventor and the hard work of the employees and to "separate the weapon as a weapon of murder from the people who are producing it and to tell its history in our country".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] On 19 September 2017 a 9 metres (30 ft) monument of Kalashnikov was unveiled in central Moscow.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] A protester, later detained by police, attempted to unfurl a banner reading "a creator of weapons is a creator of death".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The proliferation of this weapon is reflected by more than just numbers.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 is included on the flag of Mozambique and its emblem, an acknowledgment that the country gained its independence in large part through the effective use of their AK-47s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It is also found in the coats of arms of East Timor, Zimbabwe and the revolution era Burkina Faso, as well as in the flags of Hezbollah, Syrian Resistance, FARC-EP, the New People's Army, TKP/TIKKO and the International Revolutionary People's Guerrilla Forces.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] US and Western Europe countries frequently associate the AK-47 with their enemies, both Cold War era and present-day.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] For example, Western works of fiction (movies, television, novels, video games) often portray criminals, gang members, insurgents, and terrorists using AK-47s as the weapon of choice.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Conversely, throughout the developing world, the AK-47 can be positively attributed with revolutionaries against foreign occupation, imperialism, or colonialism.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In Ireland the AK-47 is associated with The Troubles due to its extensive use by republican paramilitaries during this period.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In 2013, a decommissioned AK-47 was included in the *A History of Ireland in 100 Objects* collection.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] The AK-47 made an appearance in US popular culture as a recurring focus in the Nicolas Cage film *Lord of War* (2005).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] Numerous monologues in the movie focus on the weapon, and its effects on global conflict and the gun running market.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In Iraq and Afghanistan, private military company contractors from the UK and other countries used the AK-47 and its variants along with Western firearms such as the AR-15.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In 2006, the Colombian musician and peace activist César López devised the *escopetarra*, an AK converted into a guitar.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] One sold for US$17,000 in a fundraiser held to benefit the victims of anti-personnel mines, while another was exhibited at the United Nations' Conference on Disarmament.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] In Mexico, the AK-47 is known as "Cuerno de Chivo" (literally "Goat's Horn") because of its curved magazine design.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It is one of the weapons of choice of Mexican drug cartels.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-47] It is sometimes mentioned in Mexican folk music lyrics.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The **AK-74** (Russian: Автомат Калашникова образца 1974 года, romanized: *Avtomat Kalashnikova obraztsa 1974 goda*, lit.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] 'Kalashnikov assault rifle model 1974') is an assault rifle designed by small arms designer Mikhail Kalashnikov in 1974 as a successor to the AKM.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It is chambered for the 5.45×39mm cartridge, which replaced the 7.62×39mm cartridge of Kalashnikov's earlier automatic weapons for the Soviet Armed Forces.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The rifle first saw service with Soviet forces in the Soviet–Afghan War from 1979.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The head of the Afghan bureau of the Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), the intelligence agency of Pakistan, claimed that the American Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) paid $5,000 for the first AK-74 captured by the Afghan mujahideen during the war.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] As of 2026, most countries of the former Soviet Union use the rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Licensed copies were produced in Bulgaria (AK-74, AKS-74 and AKS-74U), and in the former East Germany (MPi-AK-74N, MPi-AKS-74N, MPi-AKS-74NK).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Kryakushin's group under the design supervision of Mikhail Kalashnikov.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It is an adaptation of the 7.62×39mm AKM assault rifle and features several important design improvements.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] These improvements were primarily the result of converting the rifle to the intermediate-calibre high velocity 5.45×39mm cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In fact, some early models are reported to have been converted AKMs, re-barreled to 5.45×39mm.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Compared with the preceding AKM, the AK-74 has better effective firing range, accuracy (a main development goal), and reliability.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] About 50% of the parts in the AK-74 and AKM are the same (including pins, springs and screws).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The rifle's operation during firing and reloading is identical to that of the AKM.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The moving assembly has about 5.5 mm (0.2 in) of free travel which creates a delay between the initial recoil impulse of the piston and the bolt unlocking sequence, allowing gas pressures to drop to a safe level before the seal between the chamber and the bolt is broken.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Like previous Kalashnikov-pattern rifles, the AK-74 does not have a gas valve; excess gases are ventilated through a series of radial ports in the gas cylinder.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Since the Kalashnikov operating system offers no primary extraction upon bolt rotation, the 5.45×39mm AK-74 bolt has a larger extractor claw than the 7.62×39mm AKM for increased extraction reliability.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Other minor modifications were made to the bolt and carrier assembly.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The rifle received a new barrel with a chrome-lined bore and 4 right-hand grooves at a 200 mm (1:7.87 in) or 37 calibers rifling twist rate.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The front sight base and gas block were redesigned.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The gas block contains a gas channel that is installed at a 90° angle in relation to the bore axis to reduce bullet shear at the port hole.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A pair of support brackets are cast into the gas block assembly and are used to attach a BG-15c or GP-25 underslung 40 mm grenade launcher.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Like the AK-47 and AKM, the muzzle is threaded for the installation of various muzzle devices such as the standard muzzle brake or a blank-firing adaptor, while a spring-loaded detent pin held in the front sight post prevents them from unscrewing while firing.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] However the muzzle threads have been relocated to the front sight base for both easier and more economic replacement in case of thread damage.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A flat plate near the end of the brake produces a forward thrust when emerging exhaust gases strike its surface, greatly reducing recoil.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The muzzle brake prevents backblast from reaching the firer, although it is reported to be harsh on bystanders as the muzzle gases are dispersed to the sides.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The standard-issue AK-74 muzzle brake has been subtly revised several times since the 1970s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74 uses an adjustable notched rear tangent iron sight calibrated in 100 m (109 yd) increments from 100 to 1,000 m (109 to 1,094 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Horizontal adjustment requires a special drift tool and is done by the armoury before issue or if the need arises by an armourer after issue.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The "point-blank range" battle zero setting "*П*" standing for *постоянная* (constant/consistent/permanent) the 5.45×39mm AK-74 rear tangent sight element corresponds to a 400 m (437 yd) zero, compared with the 300 m (328 yd) zero for 7.62×39mm AKs.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] For the AK-74 combined with the 7N6 or 7N10 service cartridges the 400 m battle zero setting point-blank range limits the apparent "bullet rise" within approximately −5 to +38 cm (−2.0 to 15.0 in) under the line of sight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] At the corresponding 440 m (481 yd) maximum point-blank range the bullet will have dropped to approximately −21 cm (−8.3 in) relative to the line of sight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] While most Russian and CIS armed forces use the AK-74 in its basic configuration with iron sights, many magnified and non-magnified optical sights are available for designated marksmen and other special purpose troops in their respective militaries.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] For the 5.45×39mm AK-74, the East German **Zeiss ZFK 4×25**, **USP-1 (1P29)**, Belorussian BelOMO **PO 3.5×21P**, **PO 4×24P**, 1P78 Kashtan and the newest **1P87 Valdai** dedicated side rail mounted optical sights were developed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] These optical sights are primarily designed for rapid target acquisition and first round hits out to 400 m, but by various means these optical sights also offer bullet drop compensation (BDC) (sometimes referred to as ballistic elevation) for aiming at more distant targets.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The BDC feature compensates for the effect of gravity on the bullet at given distances (referred to as "bullet drop") in flat fire scenarios.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The feature must be tuned for the particular ballistic trajectory of a particular combination of gun and cartridge at a predefined muzzle velocity and air density.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The standard Russian side rail mounted optical sight was the 4×26 **1P29** Universal sight for small arms.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It was copied from and hence similar to the British SUIT (Sight Unit Infantry, Trilux).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] When mounted the 1P29 sight is positioned centered above the receiver at a height that allows the use of the iron sights.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It weighs 0.8 kg, offers 4× magnification with a field of view of 8° and 35 mm eye relief.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The 1P29 is issued with a canvas pouch, a lens cleaning cloth, combination tool, two rubber eyecups, two eyecup clamps and three different bullet drop compensation (BDC) cams for the AK-74/AN-94, RPK-74 and PK machine gun.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The 1P29 is intended for quickly engaging point and area targets at various ranges and is zeroed for both windage and elevation at 400 m (437 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] On the right side of the field of view a stadiametric rangefinder is incorporated that can be used to determine the distance from a 1.5 meters (4 ft 11.1 in) tall object from 400 to 1,200 m (437 to 1,312 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The reticle is an inverted aiming post in the top half of the field of view and is tritium-illuminated for low-light condition aiming.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The current Russian standard side rail mounted optical sight for the AK-74M is the 2.8×17 **1P78 Kashtan**, an aiming optic similar to the American ACOG.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] When mounted the 1P78 sight is positioned centered above the receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It weighs 0.5 kg, offers 2.8× magnification with a field of view of 13° and 32 mm eye relief.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The 1P78 is intended for quickly engaging point and area targets at various ranges and is zeroed for both windage and elevation at 400 m (437 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A stadiametric rangefinder is incorporated that can be used to determine the distance for a soldier sized target from 400 to 700 m (437 to 766 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The reticle consist of a main 400 m "chevron" (^), a 500 m (547 yd) holdover dot and smaller additional holdover chevrons for 600 m (656 yd) and 700 m (766 yd) and is tritium-illuminated for low-light condition aiming.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74 was equipped with a new buttstock, handguard (which retained the AKM-type finger swells) and gas cylinder.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The stock has a shoulder pad different from that on the AKM, which is rubber and serrated for improved seating against the shooter.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In addition, there are lightening cuts on each side of the buttstock.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The buttstock, lower handguard and upper heatguard were first manufactured from laminated wood, this later changed to a synthetic fiberglass-reinforced polyamide 6 colored with "kaprozol brown 4K" disperse dye, the color of which is usually referred to as "Russian Plum".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The introduction of the new material was slow and impeded by very stringent hardness requirements of the military which no Western polymer furniture was able to satisfy as of 1980.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74 gas tube has a spring washer attached to its rear end designed to retain the gas tube more securely.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The lower handguard is fitted with a leaf spring that reduces play in the rifle's lateral axis by keeping the wood tensioned between the receiver and the handguard retainer.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The receiver remains nearly identical to that of the AKM; it is a U-shaped 1 mm (0.04 in) thick sheet steel pressing supported extensively by pins and rivets.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The internal guide rails on which the bolt carrier travels are stamped and spot welded to the inside of the receiver housing.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Minor changes were made to the front barrel and rear stock trunnions as well as the magazine well.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] All external metal surfaces are coated with a glossy black enamel paint.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Tests measured the free recoil energy delivered by the 5.45×39mm AK-74 rifle at 3.39 J (2.50 ft⋅lb), compared with 7.19 J (5.30 ft⋅lb) delivered by the 7.62×39mm in the AKM.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Early 5.45×39mm ballistics tests demonstrated a pronounced tumbling effect with high speed cameras.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Some Western authorities believed this bullet was designed to tumble in flesh to increase wounding potential.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] At the time, it was believed that yawing and cavitation of projectiles were primarily responsible for tissue damage.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Martin Fackler conducted a study with an AK-74 assault rifle using live pigs and ballistic gelatin; "The result of our preset test indicate that the AK-74 bullet acts in the manner expected of a full-metal-cased military ammunition – it does not deform or fragment when striking soft tissues".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Most organs and tissue were too flexible to be severely damaged by the temporary cavity effect caused by yaw and cavitation of a projectile.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] With the 5.45 mm bullet, tumbling produced a temporary cavity twice, at depths of 100 mm (3.9 in) and 350 mm (13.8 in).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] This is similar to (but more rapid than) modern 7.62×39mm ammunition and to (non-fragmenting) 5.56×45mm NATO ammunition.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The original steel-reinforced 30-round AK-74 detachable box magazine was similar to that of the AKM, except for minor dimensional changes required by the 5.45×39mm cartridge.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Noted for their durability, these magazines did however compromise the rifle's camouflage and lacked the small horizontal reinforcing ribs running down both sides of the magazine body near the front that were added on all later AK-74 magazine generations.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A second generation steel-reinforced dark-brown (color shades vary from maroon to plum to near black) 30-round magazine was introduced in the early 1980s, fabricated from ABS plastic.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The third generation steel-reinforced 30-round AK-74 magazine is similar to the second generation, but is darker colored and has a matte nonreflective surface finish.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] With the introduction of the AK-74M the fourth generation of steel-reinforced matte true black nonreflective surface finished 30-round AK-74 magazines was introduced.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] All AK-74 magazines have a raised horizontal rib on each side of the rear lug to prevent their use in a 7.62×39mm AK.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The magazines can be quickly recharged from stripper clips.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The empty weight of a 30-round AK-74 box magazine is 230 g (8.1 oz).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The 45-round plastic box magazine of the RPK-74 light machine gun is also interchangeable with that of the AK-74.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The empty weight of a 45-round RPK-74 box magazine is 300 g (11 oz).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Further 60-round and later 50-round quad-stack 5.45×39mm casket magazines were developed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Note: All, 7.62×39mm AK magazines are backwards compatible with older AK variants.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Note *: 10.12 kg (22.3 lb) is the maximum amount of ammo that the average soldier can comfortably carry.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It also allows for best comparison of the three most common 7.62×39mm AK platform magazines and the 5.45×39mm AK-74 magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Accessories supplied with the military version of the rifle include a 6H4 or 6H5 type bayonet, a quick-loading device, three spare magazines, four 15-round stripper clips, maintenance kit, cleaning rod and sling.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The bayonet is installed by slipping the muzzle ring around the flash hider and latching the handle down on the bayonet lug under the front sight base.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The 6H5 AK-74 bayonet introduced in 1983 represents a further refinement of the 6H4 AKM bayonet.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It introduced a radical blade cross-section, that has a flat milled on one side near the edge and a corresponding flat milled on the opposite side near the false edge.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The blade has a new spear point and an improved one-piece molded plastic grip making it a more effective fighting knife.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It also has saw-teeth on the false edge and the usual hole for use as a wire-cutter.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74 series is also available in several "night-fighting" configurations, equipped with a side dovetail rail for mounting optical sights.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] These variants, the **AK-74N**, **AKS-74N** and **AKS-74UN** can be used in conjunction with NSPU and NSPU-3 (1PN51) night sights, as well as optical sights such as the USP-1 (1P29).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The variants designated AK-74N2 and AKS-74N2 can use the multi-model night vision sight NSPUM (1PN58).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The **AKS-74** ("S"—Russian: складной; *Skladnoy*, or "foldable"), is a variant of the AK-74 equipped with a side-folding metal shoulder stock, designed primarily for use with air assault infantry and developed alongside the basic AK-74.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Unlike the AKMS's somewhat fragile underfolding stock (modeled after the MP 40 submachine gun stock), the AKS-74 stock is fabricated from stamped sheet metal struts, machine pressed into a "U" shape and assembled by punch fit and welding.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The stock has a triangular shape; it lacks the folding shoulder pad found on the AKMS stock and is folded to the left side of the receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The hinged stock is securely locked in its extended position by a spring-loaded button catch located at the rear of the receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] When folded, the stock is held closed by a spring-loaded capture hook situated on the left side at the front of the receiver housing.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A rear-mounted sling swivel is also provided on the right side at the beginning of the stock frame.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It retains the pistol grip reinforcement plate the AKMS used, though due to the less complex rear trunnion, only has one riveting hole in place of the three on the AKMS.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In 1991, the Izhmash factory in the city of Izhevsk began full-scale production of a modernised variant of the AK-74—the **AK-74M** ("М"—Russian: Модернизи́рованный, romanized: *Modernizírovanny*, lit.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] 'modernised') assault rifle that offers more versatility compared with its predecessor.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] As a result, pistol grip reinforcement plates that were once exclusively used on the folding stock variants are standard on all AK-74Ms.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] To reduce production costs, barrel hardware, such as the front sight base and gas block, are dimple pressed on to the barrel instead of pinned on (commercial semi-auto variants are still pinned on to maintain user serviceability).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Other economic changes include omission of lightening cuts on the front sight block and gas piston as well as a stamped gas tube release lever, replacing the milled one.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The bullet guide and bolt guide were also separated, with the bolt guide becoming a simple bump held in place on the left side of the receiver with an additional rivet (often called a "bump rivet" because of this) making it easier to replace in case of wear.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Each AK-74M is fitted with a side-rail bracket for mounting optics that is a simplified version of the 74N mount with less machining cuts.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74M would have been adopted by the Soviet Union as the standard service rifle, and has been accepted as the new service rifle of the Russian Federation.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The Kalashnikov Concern has further developed three sets of additional equipment for the modernization of 5.45×39mm and 7.62×39mm chambered AK-pattern assault rifles for normal military units, reconnaissance units, and special forces units.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In 2015, the Kalashnikov Concern announced a contract with the Russian Ministry of Defence to deliver upgrade kits for their AK-74M assault rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In 1973, a design competition (codenamed "Modern"—Модерн) was started for the adoption of a fully automatic carbine.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Soviet planners drew from the unsolicited design AO-46 built in 1969 by Peter Andreevich Tkachev, which weighed only 1.9 kg.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The TTT specifications required a weight no greater than 2.2 kg (4.9 lb), a length of 75 cm (29.5 in)/45 cm (17.7 in) with the stock unfolded/folded, and an effective firing range of 500 m (547 yd).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The competition was joined by designs of Mikhail Kalashnikov (PP1), Igor Stechkin (TKB-0116), S.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Konstantinov (AEK-958), and Yevgeny Dragunov (who called his model "MA").
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Kalashnikov also presented an additional design (A1-75) which differed from PP1 by having a modified muzzle for flash and noise suppression.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In 1977, the GRAU decided to adopt Kalashnikov's model, which was largely a shortened AKS-74, because its performance was no worse than the competition, and promised significant production cost savings by utilizing existing equipment for the AK-74 line.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A final round of large scale testing with Kalashnikov's model was performed by airborne divisions in the Transcaucasian Military District in March 1977.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U ("U"—Russian: укороченный; *Ukorochenniy*, or "shortened") was officially adopted in 1979, and given the official, but seldom used GRAU designation 6P26.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U bridges the tactical deployment gap between a submachine gun and an assault rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It was intended for use mainly with special forces, airborne infantry, rear-echelon support units, helicopter and armored vehicle crews.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It has been augmented and replaced by various submachine guns, and the less compact AK-105 carbine in Russian military service.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] It is commonly used by law enforcement; for example, each urban police foot patrol is issued at least one.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U's compact dimensions were achieved by using a short 206.5 mm (8.1 in) barrel (this forced designers to simultaneously reduce the gas piston operating rod to an appropriate length).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Due to the shortening of the operating mechanism, the cyclic rate rose slightly to around 700 rounds per minute.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In order to effectively stabilize projectiles, the barrel's twist rate was increased from 200 mm (1:7.87 in) or 37 calibers rifling twist rate to 160 mm (1:6.3 in) or 29.6 calibers rifling twist rate to adapt the AKS-74U for muzzle velocities of 720 m/s (2,362 ft/s) and higher.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The chrome-lined muzzle booster also burns any remaining propellant, which would normally reduce muzzle blast.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] However, due to the extremely short barrel and conical end of the booster, the muzzle blast is nevertheless extremely large and visible.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The muzzle device locks into the gas block with a spring-loaded detent pin and features two parallel notches cut into the edge of the flash hider cone, used for unscrewing it using the cleaning rod.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Unlike most Kalashnikov variants there is no provision to store the cleaning rod under the barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The front sight was integrated into the gas block/forward sling loop.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The sight height above the bore axis is also approximately 3 mm (0.1 in) higher than the AK-74, due to the combined front sight/gas block, rear sight configuration.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U has a different rear sight composed of a U-shaped flip sight on the top cover instead of the standard sliding notch tangent rear sight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] This rear sight has two settings: "*П*" standing for *постоянная* (constant) corresponding to a 350 m (383 yd) "point-blank range" battle zero setting and "4-5" (used for firing at distances between 400–500 m (437–547 yd)).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The rear sight is housed in a semi-shrouded protective enclosure that is riveted to the receiver's spring-loaded top cover.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] This top cover hinges from a barrel trunnion (hinging where the rear sight on a normal AK74 is located), pivoting forward when opened, which also works to unlock the gas tube cover.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Both the gas tube and handguard are also of a new type and are wider and shorter than the analogous parts in the AKS-74.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] For the AKS-74s combined with the 7N6 or 7N10 service cartridges the 350 m battle zero setting limits the apparent "bullet rise" within approximately −5 to +42 cm (−2.0 to 16.5 in) relative to the line of sight.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Soldiers are instructed to fire at any target within this range by simply placing the sights on the center of mass (the belt buckle) of the enemy target.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U cannot mount a bayonet or standard under-barrel grenade launcher.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] However, a suppressed 30 mm BS-1 grenade launcher was developed specifically for that platform that fires a high-explosive dual purpose (HEDP) grenade.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The grenades for the BS-1 are launched by special blank cartridges that are inserted into the grenade launcher via a detachable magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The majority of AKS-74U carbines were manufactured at the Tula Arms Factory rather than Izhmash.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] There were some accessories produced for the AKS-74U including a plastic thigh holster and (shorter than standard) 20-round AK-74 type magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The rifle utilizes a proprietary 25 mm wide sling that differs from the standard 35 mm AK sling also in construction.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U also exists in a version featuring modernized synthetic furniture made from a black, glass-filled polyamide.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U was also used as the basis for several other unique weapons, including the bullpup OTs-14 Groza specialist carbine which is now in limited service in the Russian military, and the Gepard series of multi-caliber submachine guns (none of which evolved past prototype stage).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In the United States, the AKS-74U is sometimes called a "Krinkov".
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] A hypothesis was circulating that the name came from the Mujahideen who supposedly had captured a high-ranking Soviet officer armed with an AKS-74U, and that they had named it after him.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] However, investigation by Patrick Sweeney could not confirm this hypothesis, for no Soviet officer with a resembling name was captured in Afghanistan.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Chivers reported that the gun was nicknamed "the Osama" in jihadist circles, after Osama bin Laden was photographed next to an AKS-74U.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Research by The Firearm Blog published in 2016 suggests that the name "Krinkov" is a Pashtun invention that came to the United States with accounts of the Mujahideen.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AKS-74U is approximately 3 oz (85 g) lighter than the NATO equivalent XM177, and 10.2 in (260 mm) shorter with the stock folded.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The **AKS-74UB** ("B"—Russian: бесшумный; *Besshumniy* or "silent") is a sound-suppressed variant of the AKS-74U adapted for use with the PBS-4 suppressor (used in combination with subsonic 5.45×39mm *7U1* Russian ammunition).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74M is manufactured under license by the Ministry of Defence Industry of Azerbaijan.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Locally produced AK-74, AKS-74 and AKS-74U were used by the Bulgarian Armed Forces.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] They were phased out in the military in favor of the older AK-47 and AKM rifles, presumably because of the wider availability of 7.62x39mm in Bulgaria.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Some were inherited by the Ministry of Interior but were "banned from police use" in the 90s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74 is manufactured locally in Romania as the PA md.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-74 is manufactured locally in North Korea as the Type-88.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Sources suggest that it was made with technical assistance from China.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In East Germany, the AK-74, AKS-74 and AKS-74U were manufactured locally as the MPi-AK-74N, MPi-AKS-74N, and MPi-AKS-74NK.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Even with the differences in the above table all of these firearms are made to similar specifications.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] These original AK-100 series firearms were introduced in 1994 and are categorized by all having black polymer handguards, folding polymer stocks, and use of AK-74M internal systems.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-101, AK-102, AK-103 and AK-104 were designed primarily for export, while the AK-105 was developed for replacing the shorter barreled AKS-74U.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-105 is used by the Russian Army and Ministry of Internal Affairs.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] These have a technically differing balanced recoil system to reduce felt recoil and muzzle rise.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] This balanced recoil system designed by Yuriy K.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Alexandrov for Kalashnikov-pattern rifles is a significant change to the Kalashnikov operating system of the 1940s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The operating system of these new rifles was derived from the AL-7 experimental rifle of the early 1970s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Since their development, these rifles met little commercial success.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-100M/AK-200 rifle family was initially conceived around 2009 as an improved variant of the basic AK-100 series.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Most improvements centered on ergonomic improvements and mounting systems for accessories.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The development of the AK-200 family was stopped around 2011, but resumed around 2016.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In 2017, Kalashnikov unveiled the modernised versions of the AK-100 family of rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-200 series are based on the AK-100 series and the AK-12.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] They can be chambered in 5.45×39mm, 5.56×45mm NATO and 7.62×39mm, and use a barrel and gas system assembly similar to that of the AK-74M/AK-100 rifle family.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Improvements added from the AK-12 include Picatinny rails, a new pistol grip, a new adjustable buttstock and a new flash hider.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] They feed from 30-round magazines, and are compatible with drum magazines from the RPK and RPK-74.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] After 2017 these arms were assigned AK-200 series designations.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] As of 2018, the AK-200 series rifles are offered for export sales and for domestic law enforcement users in Russia.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In 2010, the **AK-12** series of proposed prototype models were unveiled.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] They differed in weight, introduced a new recoil compensation technology and improved ergonomics.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The rear iron sight element was rail-mounted and moved to the back of the upper receiver to lengthen the sight line, and the full length of the weapon featured a Picatinny rail for mounting accessories such as aiming optics on top.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The hand guard features Picatinny rails on both sides and its underside for mounting accessories like tactical lights, laser sights and grenade launchers.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Throughout its development and evaluation stage the multiple modifications were applied to meet Russian military standards, as well as to improve upon the "range of defects" that were discovered on prototype models and to address concerns regarding the cost of earlier prototypes.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In September 2016 the prototype models were replaced by the final production models of the AK-12 (chambered in 5.45×39mm) and AK-15 (chambered in 7.62×39mm) assault rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Parallel developments are the RPK-16 light machine gun and the AM-17 compact assault rifle (both chambered in 5.45×39mm).
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-12, AK-15 and RPK-16 technically strongly resembles the AK-74M, AK-100 series and RPK-74M than the earlier prototypes and the arms manufacturer Kalashnikov concern hopes they will replace these Russian service guns.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In late 2016 it was reported the AK-12 production model was undergoing troop trials with the Russian Army, where it competes against the Degtyarov A-545 balanced action assault rifle in Ratnik program trials.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] The AK-12 completed its operational testing and passed military field tests in June 2017, paving the way to Russian Army adoption, potentially under the Ratnik program.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] Both AK-12 and AK-15 completed testing in December 2017.
[src:airsoft-gun/ak-74] In January 2018 it was announced that the AK-12 and AK-15 have been adopted by the Russian military.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] An **AR-15–style rifle** is a lightweight semi-automatic rifle based on or similar to the Colt AR-15 design.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The Colt model removed the selective fire feature of its predecessor, the original ArmaLite AR-15, which is a scaled-down derivative of the AR-10 design (by Eugene Stoner).
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] It is closely related to the military M16 rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] ArmaLite sold the patent and trademarks for both to Colt's Manufacturing Company in 1959 after the military rejected the design in favor of the M14.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] After most of the patents for the Colt AR-15 expired in 1977, many firearm manufacturers began to produce copies of the rifle under various names.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] While the patents are expired, Colt has retained the trademark to the *AR-15* name and is the sole manufacturer able to label their firearms as such.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] From 1994 to 2004, the Federal Assault Weapons Ban restricted the sale of the Colt AR-15 and some derivatives in the United States, although it did not affect rifles with fewer listed features.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] After the phrase "**modern sporting rifles**", to be used synonymously with the AR-15 style, was coined in 2009 by the US National Shooting Sports Foundation (NSSF), a firearms trade association, it was quickly adopted by much of the industry.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Beginning in the 2010s, AR-15–style rifles became one of the "most beloved and most vilified rifles" in the United States, according to *The New York Times*; the rifles have gained infamy due in part to their use in high-profile mass shootings.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Promoted as "America's rifle" by the National Rifle Association of America, their popularity is partially attributable to active restrictions, or proposals to ban or restrict them.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] They are emblematic as being on the frontline of the debate over U.S. gun control.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Different sources attribute the letters "AR" in AR-15 to different origins in the early history of the rifle by its manufacturer, ArmaLite.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] According to the company's website, it stood for "ArmaLite Rifle".
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] According to Eugene Stoner's business partner, Jim Sullivan , the letters "AR" stood for the first two letters of the company's name, while according to Stoner's daughter and son-in-law it stood for "ArmaLite Research".
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] "AR-15" is most-commonly used to refer *only* to the civilian semi-automatic variants of the rifle which lack the fully automatic function.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A common misconception is that "AR" is an abbreviation for "assault rifle" or "automatic rifle", perhaps because of the weapon's inclusion in the Federal Assault Weapons Ban in 1994, or because the ArmaLite AR-15 was originally designed to replace the M14 rifle in the Vietnam War.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The AR-15 is closely related to the military M16 and M4 carbine rifles, which all share the same core design.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A lighter weight selective fire variant of the AR-10 was designed in 1958 for military use and designated the ArmaLite model 15, or AR-15.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Due to financial problems and limitations in terms of manpower and production capacity, ArmaLite sold the AR-15 and AR-10 designs and trademarks to Colt in 1959.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] In 1964, Colt began selling its own version with an improved semi-automatic design known as the Colt AR-15.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] After Colt's patents expired in 1977, an active marketplace emerged for other manufacturers to produce and sell their own semi-automatic AR-15–style rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Some versions of the AR-15 were classified as "assault weapons" and banned under the Federal Assault Weapons Ban in 1994 within the United States.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] In 2009, the term "modern sporting rifle" was coined by the National Shooting Sports Foundation for its survey that year as a marketing term used by the firearms industry to describe modular semi-automatic rifles including AR-15s.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Today, nearly every major firearm manufacturer produces its own generic AR-15–style rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] As Colt continues to own and use the AR-15 trademark for its line of AR-15 variants, other manufacturers must use their own model numbers and names to market their AR-15–style rifles for commercial sale.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Under US law, a firearm with a barrel length of less than 16 inches (41 cm) and an overall length (OAL) of less than 26 inches (66 cm), that was not made from a rifle (including through modification), is not considered to be a short-barreled rifle.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] As the inclusion of a shoulder stock constitutes "intent to fire from the shoulder" and thus reclassifies the firearm as a rifle, many gun manufacturers offer AR-15–style "pistol" versions that are manufactured to be sold stockless or with a stabilizing pistol brace.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] If a firearm was originally manufactured as a rifle, it can't be converted into a pistol.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] However, if the firearm was originally a pistol, the resulting firearm with an attached shoulder stock is not an NFA firearm if it has a barrel of 16 in (410 mm) or more in length, and such rifle may be reconfigured as a pistol legally.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The lower receiver alone is legally defined as a firearm under United States federal law.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] However, the legality of this definition has been disputed in conflicting court rulings as to whether the AR-15 lower receiver matches the legal definition set forth in 27 CFR § 479.11, with some lower courts disagreeing while a 2021 case from the Eighth Circuit found otherwise.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] While most earlier breech-loading rifles had a single receiver housing both the trigger and reloading mechanism, an innovative feature of the AR-15 was modular construction to simplify substitution of parts and avoid need for arsenal facilities for most repairs of malfunctioning military rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A distinctive two-part receiver is used by both military and sporting AR-15–style rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Due to the vast assortment of aftermarket parts and accessories available, AR-15–style rifles have also been referred to as "the Swiss Army knife of rifles", "Barbie Dolls for Guys", or "LEGOs for adults".
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] These more or less interchangeable modules are a defining characteristic of AR-15–style rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The lower receiver includes the trigger guard in front of the detachable pistol grip, and behind the magazine well.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Lower receivers may be bought "stripped"—a single solid part and legally a firearm in the United States, albeit nonfunctional, with no fire control group or lower parts kit installed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] End users may install their own choice of fire control group and lower parts kit.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The lower receiver holds the trigger assembly including the hammer, and is the attachment point for the buttstock.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The lower receiver is attached to the upper receiver by two removable pins.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Disassembly for cleaning or repair of malfunctions requires disengaging these pins from the upper receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Releasing the rear take-down pin allows the receiver to be opened by rotation around the forward pivot pin as a hinge.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Releasing the front pin as well allows the upper receiver to be separated from the lower for cleaning, maintenance or change of caliber by installation of a different upper receiver assembly.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The upper receiver contains the bolt carrier assembly and is attached to the barrel assembly.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Sights may be attached to the upper receiver or the barrel assembly.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A handguard usually encloses the barrel and is attached to the upper receiver, and depending on the handguard, also attached to the barrel's gas block.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] AR-15–style rifles may have folding or collapsible stocks which reduce the overall length of the rifle when folded, although some designs of the stock folding device may not allow the firearm to be fired until unfolded, or only fire once until unfolded.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The standard design includes a gas block and tube to vent burnt powder gas back into the bolt carrier assembly where it expands in a variable volume chamber forcing the bolt open to eject the spent cartridge case.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The buffer spring in the buttstock then pushes the bolt closed after picking up a new cartridge from the magazine.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] This Stoner bolt and carrier piston system has the disadvantage of venting un-burned smokeless powder residue into the receiver where it may ultimately accumulate in quantities causing malfunctions.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Some AR-15–style rifles use an alternative short-stroke gas piston design borrowed from the ArmaLite AR-18, where a metal rod pushes against the bolt carrier, driven by a piston located just behind the barrel gas port.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] This piston design keeps the rifle cleaner by not exhausting in to the receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Other AR-15–style rifles feature redesigned gas systems so the rifle is "over-the-beach capable", allowing it fire safely as quickly as possible after being submerged in water.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The original design features a free-floating firing pin.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] To theoretically reduce the risk of slam-firing, the HK416 and its civilian variant MR556 feature a proprietary firing pin safety in the bolt.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Such firing pin safeties may obstruct the upper from working with standard AR-15-type full height hammers located in the fire control group of the lower.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Most rifles eject spent cartridges from the right side of the receiver away from right-handed shooters who place the butt against the right shoulder while sighting with the right eye and using a finger of the right hand to pull the trigger.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] When the M16A2 was adopted by the Army in 1986, it incorporated a built-in brass deflector to keep ejected cartridges from hitting the user.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Most civilian variants also copy that feature.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The modular design of AR-15–style rifles has encouraged several manufacturers to offer specialized parts including leftward ejecting upper receivers and left-handed bolts/bolt carriers for converting right-handed AR-15–style rifles for left-handed use.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Ambidextrous lower receivers, magazine releases, and safety selectors have also been produced, allowing release of the magazine from the left side, closing of the bolt from the right side, and operation of the safety from the right side, respectively.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Some AR-15–style rifles limit use of detachable magazines to comply with state regulations.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Nearly all versions of the civilian AR-15 have a pistol grip like the military versions, but as the pistol grip is generally removable, grips and stocks that comply with various restrictions are available.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] While AR-15–style rifles are banned in New York City, the FightLite SCR has been explicitly allowed, even though it accepts standard AR-15 upper receivers.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The SCR lower receiver differs from the standard AR-15 lower receiver in that it uses a Monte Carlo stock instead of a pistol grip, which may allow it to be legally possessed in jurisdictions with assault weapon restrictions in place.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] It also uses a proprietary bolt carrier due to the angled buffer tube, and a proprietary fire control group that moves the trigger rearward.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A few manufactures offer bolt action or pump action AR-15–style rifles incapable of semi-automatic fire.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] These are most commonly marketed in jurisdictions where ownership of semi-automatic centerfire rifles is heavily restricted, such as in the United Kingdom and Australia.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The semi-automatic civilian AR-15 was introduced by Colt in 1963.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The primary distinction between the civilian semi-automatic rifles and the military assault rifles is select fire.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Military models are produced with multiple firing modes: semi-automatic fire, fully automatic fire mode and/or burst fire mode, in which the rifle fires multiple rounds in succession when the trigger is depressed a single time.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Most components are interchangeable between semi-auto and select fire rifles including magazines, sights, upper receiver, barrels and accessories.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The military M4 carbine typically uses a 14.5-inch (37 cm) barrel.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Civilian rifles commonly have 16-inch (41 cm) or longer barrels to comply with the National Firearms Act.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] To prevent a civilian semi-automatic AR-15 from being readily converted for use with the select fire components, several features were changed.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Parts changed include the lower receiver, bolt carrier, hammer, trigger, disconnector, and safety/mode selector.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The semi-automatic bolt carrier has a longer lightening slot to prevent the bolt's engagement with an automatic sear.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Due to a decrease in mass, the buffer spring is heavier.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] On the select-fire version, the hammer has an extra spur which interacts with the additional auto-sear that holds it back until the bolt carrier group is fully in battery, when the automatic fire is selected.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Using a portion of the select fire parts in a semi-automatic rifle will not enable a select fire option (this requires a registered part with the ATF).
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Lower receivers that are select-fire are identified by a pinhole above the safety/mode selection switch.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] As designed by Colt, the pins supporting the semi-auto trigger and hammer in the lower receiver are larger than those used in the military rifle to prevent interchangeability between semi-automatic and select-fire components.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The pivot pin may also be slightly larger in diameter.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The first version produced for commercial sale by Colt was the SP1 model AR-15 Sporter in .223 Remington, with a 20-inch (51 cm) barrel and issued with five-round magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Initial sales of the Colt AR-15 were slow, primarily due to its fixed sights and carry handle that made scopes difficult to mount and awkward to use.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Military development of compact military AR-15 carbines encouraged production of a 16-inch (41 cm) barreled civilian SP1 carbine with a collapsible buttstock beginning in 1977.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] These carbines have become popular for police use in confined urban spaces, and the collapsible buttstock compensates for the additional thickness of body armor.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The shorter barrel reduced bullet velocity by about five percent, and bullet energy by about 10%.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The shorter barrel required moving the gas port closer to the chamber, exposing the self-loading system to higher pressures and temperatures which increased stress on moving parts like the bolt lugs and extractor.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Although Colt offered a heavier 20-inch (51 cm) barrel for improved accuracy beginning in 1986, increased barrel weight may impair ergonomic balance; so shorter barrels have dominated recent rifle production.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] In the 1990s, sales of AR-15–style rifles increased dramatically, partly as a result of the introduction of the flat top upper receiver (M4 variant) which allowed scopes and sighting devices to be easily mounted as well as new features such as free floating hand guards that increased accuracy.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] While only a handful of companies were manufacturing these rifles in 1994, by the 21st century the number of AR-15–style rifles had more than doubled.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] From 2000 to 2015, the number of manufacturers of AR-15–style rifles increased from 29 to an estimated 500.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] AR-15–style rifles are now available in a wide range of configurations and calibers from a large number of manufacturers.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] These configurations range from standard full-sizes rifles with 20-inch (51 cm) barrels, to short carbine-length models with 16-inch (41 cm) barrels, adjustable length stocks and optical sights, to long range target models with 24-inch (61 cm) barrels, bipods and high-powered scopes.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] However, in 2020, Colt resumed production of the AR-15, following a surge in demand in the United States consumer market.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Estimates vary as to how many of the rifles are owned in the United States.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The National Shooting Sports Foundation estimated in 2016 that approximately 5 million to 10 million AR-15–style rifles existed in the U.S. within the broader total of the 300 million firearms owned by Americans.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] According to the National Shooting Sports Foundation, there were an estimated 24.4 million AR-15s in private circulation in the United States in 2020.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] According to a 2021 Georgetown University poll of gun owners in the US, 24.6 million persons have an AR-15 or a comparable firearm in their possession.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Many hunters prefer using AR-15–style rifles because of their versatility, accuracy, wide variety of available features, and wide variety of calibers (see below).
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Collapsible stocks are convenient for hunters who pack their rifles into remote hunting locations or for length of pull adjustments to fit any sized hunter.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Construction with lightweight polymers and corrosion-resistant alloys makes these rifles preferred for hunting in moist environments with less concern about rusting or warping wood stocks.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Positioning of the AR-15 safety is an improvement over traditional bolt action hunting rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Many states require hunters to use reduced-capacity magazines.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] If a hunter misses with a first shot, the self-loading feature enables rapid follow-up shots against dangerous animals like feral pigs or rapidly moving animals like jackrabbits.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Hunters shooting larger game animals often use upper receivers and barrels adapted for larger cartridges or heavier bullets.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Several states prohibit the use of .22 caliber cartridges like the .223 Remington on large game.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Since the upper and lower receivers may be swapped between rifles, forensic firearm examination of bullets and spent cartridges may reveal distinguishing marks from the barrel and upper receiver group without identifying the lower receiver for which legal records may be available.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] An individual may use several upper receiver groups with the same lower receiver.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] These upper receiver groups may have differing barrel lengths and sights and may fire different cartridges.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A hunter with a single lower receiver might have one upper receiver with a .223 Remington barrel and telescopic sight for varmint hunting in the open country and another upper receiver with a .458 SOCOM barrel and iron sights for big-game hunting in brushy woodland.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The dimensions of upper and lower receivers originally designed for the 5.56×45mm NATO cartridge impose an overall length limit and diameter limits when adapting modules for other cartridges included in this list of AR platform cartridges.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The same magazine in the lower receiver group may hold differing numbers of different cartridges.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Most firearm-related homicides in the United States involve handguns.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] A 2019 Pew Research study found that 3% of US gun deaths were committed using rifles, a category which includes AR-15–style rifles.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] According to a 2013 analysis by Mayors Against Illegal Guns, 14 out of 93 mass shootings involved high-capacity magazines or assault weapons.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] AR-15–style rifles have played a prominent role in many high-profile mass shootings in the U.S. and have come to be widely characterized as the weapon of choice for perpetrators of these crimes.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] AR-15 or AR-15-style rifles were the primary weapons used in four of the 10 deadliest mass shootings in modern American history: the 2012 Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting, the 2017 Las Vegas shooting, the 2017 Sutherland Springs church shooting, and the 2022 Robb Elementary School shooting.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] The first known use of an AR-15–style rifle in a mass shooting was in 2007, during the Crandon shooting, according to *Mother Jones*'s mass shooting database.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] Gun expert Dean Hazen and mass murder researcher Pete Blair claim that mass shooters' gun choices have less to do with the AR-15's specific characteristics but rather with familiarity and a copycat effect.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] On July 13, 2024, at a Trump rally in Butler, Pennsylvania, Thomas Matthew Crooks used an AR-15–style rifle in an assassination attempt on then-former president Donald Trump.
[src:airsoft-gun/ar-15-style-rifle] After the 2020 Nova Scotia attacks, the deadliest rampage by a single person in Canadian history, Canada banned a class of firearms, including the AR-15.
